<DIV1 TYPE="prologue">
<PB REF="4">
<HEAD>PROLOGUE TO <HI>THE RAGE.</HI></HEAD>
<BYLINE>(<HI>Written by</HI> JAMES BOADEN, <HI>E&s;q.</HI>)</BYLINE>
<SP>
<STAGE>SPOKEN <HI>by Mr.</HI> HOLMAN.</STAGE>
<LG>
<L>HOW narrow is the &s;phere a modern Bays</L>
<L>Is doom'd to range, while he contrives his Plays;</L>
<L>Still urg'd by folly, Beings to explore,</L>
<L>Whom <HI>he</HI> and <HI>you</HI> &s;o often &s;aw before:</L>
<L>Precluded characters by <HI>their</HI> advance,</L>
<L>Who&s;e minds could pierce thro' Nature with a glance,</L>
<L>And &s;till of right po&s;&s;e&s;s the moral Stage</L>
<L>With le&s;&s;ons &s;tudied in a di&s;tant age;</L>
<L>In this, our gla&s;s, you yet reflected find</L>
<L>The levities which le&s;&s;en human kind:</L>
<L>The lighter follies which the Town engage,</L>
<L>All that prevail in fa&s;hion makes&mdash;the Rage;</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Yes, all! though various be the motly forms,</L>
<L>That &s;way by weak'ning, or compel in &s;torms:</L>
<L>That up to Fop evaporate the Lord;</L>
<L>Or down to Jockey &s;ink the Maid ador'd;</L>
<L>Confound di&s;tinctions, firm and frail perplex,</L>
<L>And make it difficult&mdash;to gue&s;s even &s;ex.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>But is the Rage to levity confin'd?</L>
<L>Does no ju&s;t pa&s;&s;ion &s;way the general mind?</L>
<L>Lo! the rough Veteran, whom his Country's claim,</L>
<L>Rou&s;es to vindicate her injured name!</L>
<L>The <HI>Rage</HI> is <HI>Conque&s;t</HI> which his bo&s;om fires,</L>
<L>The foe yields! then&mdash;no! then his rage expires.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>When in &s;ome dreadful conte&s;t on the wave</L>
<L>The gallant &s;eaman finds a wat'ry grave,</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<PB REF="5">
<L>E'er the la&s;t pul&s;e of ebbing life be o'er,</L>
<L>When the eye turns towards his native &s;hore,</L>
<L>This thought may ev'n the parting pang a&s;&s;uage</L>
<L>That, there&mdash;<HI>Humanity</HI> is &s;till the <HI>Rage.</HI></L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Our Author's Mu&s;e follows with fa&s;hion's gale,</L>
<L>Down a &s;mooth river an amu&s;ive &s;ail;</L>
<L>She dares no &s;ea where boi&s;terous pa&s;&s;ions &s;way,</L>
<L>Or merely dips her wing, and ha&s;tes away.</L>
<L>O may her airy toil your love engage,</L>
<L>And her new flight to plea&s;e you be&mdash;<HI>The Rage.</HI></L>
</LG>
</SP>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="epilogue">
<PB REF="6">
<HEAD>EPILOGUE TO <HI>THE RAGE.</HI></HEAD>
<BYLINE>(<HI>Written by</HI> EDWARD TOPHAM, <HI>E&s;q.</HI>)</BYLINE>
<SP>
<STAGE>SPOKEN <HI>by Mrs,</HI> MATTOCKS.</STAGE>
<LG>
<L>WELL, Gentlefolks, again your mo&s;t obedient;</L>
<L>That I'm the Epilogue is held expedient:</L>
<L>Our Bard, who for a youth well knows the Stage,</L>
<L>Thought as to &s;peaking, Women were "The Rage,"</L>
<L>And &s;aid&mdash;"Good Mrs. Mattocks, pray, advance;</L>
<L>Females mu&s;t now &s;tep forward as in France."</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>My an&s;wer was&mdash;my dear, kind Sir, have pity,</L>
<L>"Pray &s;pare the Ladies&mdash;Men &s;ecure our city.</L>
<L>"For arm'd by Parliament, to calm each fear,</L>
<L>"Huge corps of Common-Councilmen appear,</L>
<L>"Wards, Liveries, Deputies, en Militaire,</L>
<L>"Led by Lieutenant-Colonel&mdash;my Lord Mayor!</L>
<L>"Each man, (a &s;ight at which his Lady &s;woons,)</L>
<L>"Belt, &s;abre, helmet, &s;purs, and pantaloons!</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>"Dear Chuck"&mdash;&s;ays Spou&s;e&mdash;"pray &s;it at home, do yielde,</L>
<L>"Con&s;ider, Love, your age; you grow unwieldy;</L>
<L>"Good twenty &s;tone, Dear, cannot play about,</L>
<L>"Be&s;ides tho&s;e cold Jack Boots hurt Lovey's Gout."</L>
<L>"Gout! vulgar non&s;en&s;e Voman&mdash;Gout! Gad's cur&s;e,</L>
<L>"Heavy! why I'm a private of Light Hor&s;e&mdash;</L>
<L>"Dre&s;s! wheel! charge!&mdash;Could I on Hor&s;eback get</L>
<L>"I or my hor&s;e would do &s;ome mi&s;chief yet.'</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Thus, meaning no offence, in language faint,</L>
<L>The City Rage for &s;oldiering we paint.</L>
<L>But &s;ure no &s;ons of Briton, wi&s;h repre&s;t</L>
<L>That zeal which leads one man to &s;erve the re&s;t;</L>
<L>Which &s;trives due right and order to maintain,</L>
<L>Again&s;t a Chaos that would come again.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<PB REF="7">
<L>Long may &s;uch Rage in&s;pire the Engli&s;h mind!</L>
<L>In neighbouring Climes a different "Rage" we find;</L>
<L>Poor <HI>Jean Fran&ccedil;ois</HI> who &s;houts for Libert&eacute;</L>
<L>Finds Slavery &s;till the Order of the Day!</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>"Ma foi! he cries&mdash;no people ble&s;t as we</L>
<L>They force me out to fight to make me free,</L>
<L>Den! vif! alert!&mdash;begar we mu&s;t not tarry,</L>
<L>My Vife, for common good, oblige to marry:</L>
<L>She labour for the State, tant mieux pour elle,</L>
<L>She forget me&mdash;I her&mdash;c'e&s;t Bagatelle!</L>
<L>Allons au Guerre! L'eau de vie bani&s;h &s;orrow,</L>
<L>Victoire to-day&mdash;La Guillotine to-morrow!"</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Engli&s;h Tom Blunt, a dealer in &s;mall wares,</L>
<L>Who knows a bit what's pa&s;&s;ing above &s;tairs.</L>
<L>Cries&mdash;"Why in that there change of wives &s;o fa&s;t</L>
<L>"I think a good one mayhap may come at la&s;t,</L>
<L>"But in that <HI>gulleting</HI> machine, d'ye &s;ee,</L>
<L>"I've no idea how it makes one free:</L>
<L>"For my part now, whatever may be &s;aid,</L>
<L>"I'm for a little meat, and &s;afe warm bed,</L>
<L>"I does not reli&s;h freedom&mdash;when one's dead;</L>
<L>"So once for all my means and re&s;olution</L>
<L>"Go, to &s;tand by the good old Con&s;titution."</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Such and &s;o different reign with &s;overeign power,</L>
<L>The various "Rages" of the pre&s;ent hour.</L>
<L>I wi&s;h, in truth I wi&s;h in very &s;pight,</L>
<L>Your Rage may be, to &s;ee us many a night.</L>
</LG>
</SP>
</DIV1>
</FRONT>
<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="play">
<PB REF="8">
<HEAD>THE RAGE: A COMEDY.</HEAD>
<DIV2 N="1" TYPE="act">
<HEAD>ACT I.</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE I.&mdash;DARNLEY'S</HI> Garden, and view of his &s;mall Villa.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> DARNLEY <HI>and Sir</HI> GEORGE GAUNTLET.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>SIR GEORGE.</SPEAKER>
<P>AND &s;o, Darnley, you prefer this &s;olitary life, to all the joys of London&mdash;to be &s;ure you've a nice &s;nug Villa, and a charming wife here&mdash;but its dull&mdash;the &s;cene tires&mdash;it wants variety, Harry.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, Sir George.&mdash;Since I retir'd to this peaceful &s;pot, I have not had a wi&s;h be|yond it: I've been &s;o happy in that humble cottage, that when I'm doom'd to leave it, the world will be a wa&s;te, and life not have a charm!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>How you are alter'd, Darnley? When we were brother officers you were the greate&s;t rake in the regiment; but from the
<PB N="2" REF="9">time we were quarter'd at Worce&s;ter, where you fir&s;t beheld Mi&s;s Dormer&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;aw the folly of my former life; I own'd the power of her &s;uperior charms, and leaving a bu&s;y and tumultuous world, retir'd with her to this &s;eque&s;ter'd &s;cene&mdash;'tis now three years &s;ince I married.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>And from that time to this, have you liv'd in this out-of-the-way place?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes: and till you ye&s;terday honour'd me with a vi&s;it, I have not &s;een a friend within my doors&mdash;but isn't it a happy life, Sir George? Our affections have room to &s;hoot&mdash;care and di&s;tru&s;t are bani&s;h'd from our cottage, and with &s;uch a woman as Mrs. Darnley to con|ver&s;e with, what is the world to me? I can defy and &s;corn its malice.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>She's an angelic creature indeed, Darnley: and at Worce&s;ter, I had my&s;elf near|ly fallen a victim to her charms; but about your future life&mdash;do you mean to live for ever in the&s;e woods and meadows?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;would to heaven I could!&mdash;I fear I mu&s;t forego my pre&s;ent calm, and mix in active life again: When I married, I &s;old my commi&s;&s;ion, you remember, to purcha&s;e this &s;mall farm&mdash;Mrs. Darnley's portion was but a trifle, and an encrea&s;ing family has &s;o enlarg'd my expences, that unle&s;s I return to the army&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah&mdash;you want to be raking again?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;I want to &s;ecure an indepen|dence for my family&mdash;I want to &s;ee my chil|dren affluent, and to attain this, I have once more applied to my uncle Sir Paul Perpetual,
<PB N="3" REF="10">who was &s;o offended at my &s;elling out, that he has ever &s;ince abandon'd me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>What&mdash;does the old beau &s;till per&s;evere in his re&s;entment?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>His anger has encreas'd; for he writes me word; he intends marrying Lady Sa|rah Savage, on purpo&s;e to have heirs more worthy his e&s;tate:&mdash;Oh! my friend:&mdash;'tis hard, that fortune &s;hould be&s;tow &s;uch trea&s;ures, and then compel me to de&s;ert them?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>So it is: but now I think on't, this Lady Sarah Savage and her brother are my intimate friends; and as you are their neighbours, I'll introduce you and Mrs. Darn|ley to their notice&mdash;When are they expected from town?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>To day.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then we'll pay them a vi&s;it: Lady Sarah Savage &s;hall interfere with your uncle, and if that fails, her brother can ea&s;ily en&s;ure your promotion in the army&mdash;but &s;ee; here's Mrs. Darnley?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Look at her, Sir George&mdash;do you, can you blame me?&mdash;who would not act as I have done?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>I would by heav'ns!&mdash;I'd live with her in a hermitage!&mdash;die with her on a pilgrimage!&mdash;I'd&mdash;&s;death: if I don't mind, I &s;hall di&s;cover all.</P>
<STAGE>A&s;ide.</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Mrs.</HI> DARNLEY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley advancing to her.</SPEAKER>
<P>Maria!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh Harry!&mdash;I have been look|ing for you every where&mdash;I declare you're grown quite a truant&mdash;Before your friend came, you
<PB N="4" REF="11">us'd to walk with me over the farm: or ride with me to &s;ee our children; or &s;it and read to me under our favourite Beach Tree&mdash;but now&mdash;Sir George!&mdash;I beg your pardon&mdash;I didn't &s;ee you before.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Madam!</P>
<STAGE>Bowing ob&s;equiou&s;ly.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>My friend is all kindne&s;s, Maria; he has promis'd to introduce me to the honour|able Mr. Savage:</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>What:&mdash;take you to Savage hou&s;e!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay&mdash;why not:&mdash;you &s;hall go with me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;let me &s;tay here&mdash;I am not weary of my pre&s;ent life.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nor I&mdash;but 'tis a great connexion: and though not ab&s;olutely di&s;tre&s;s'd, I would improve my fortune&mdash;I would &s;ee you and my children have every comfort.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>We have, while you are with us&mdash;con&s;ider we have never liv'd a day apart, and if they lure you into fa&s;hionable &s;cenes, you'll be corrupted, Harry&mdash;you'll de&s;pi&s;e the humble roof you once rever'd, and I perhaps &s;hall be forgotten and neglected.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Never!&mdash;I cannot bear the &s;uppo|&s;ition; and while we have hearts to endure, and hands to labour, there is &s;ufficient for our cottage!&mdash;I will not go&mdash;My friend, who &s;ees my motive, I'm &s;ure, will not condemn me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;always obey the Ladies; but Darnley, I &s;ee our hor&s;es&mdash;you recollect we were to ride to &s;ee your children: &s;o, Ma|dam, I have the &s;uperlative honour&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="5" REF="12"><HI>Enter</HI> CLARA SEDLEY&mdash;<HI>a ba&s;ket of flowers is hanging on her arm, and &s;he is eating an apple.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>What, Clara!&mdash;been picking flowers my angel!&mdash;well!&mdash;I thought they had all died&mdash;all died from envy egad! ha! ha!&mdash;excu&s;e me&mdash;I never laugh but at my own wit.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do you? then you laugh very &s;el|dom, I believe.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;very often: for I take the joke though nobody el&s;e does, ha! ha!&mdash;come Darnley&mdash;adieu Ladies&mdash;I'll not run away with him!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(Exit Darnley and Sir George.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>What a coxcomb it is!&mdash;and if he wasn't a duelli&s;t into the bargain, I'd tell Mr. Darnley all my &s;u&s;picions&mdash;that I would&mdash;but he's &s;o fond of fighting, that I heard him &s;ay, he once &s;ent a man a challenge for wafering a letter in&s;tead of &s;ealing it.&mdash;I wi&s;h he was gone.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed &s;o do I, cou&s;in&mdash;Mr. Darnley is &s;o chang'd &s;ince he arriv'd&mdash;his ideas &s;o enlarg'd&mdash;he talks of vi&s;iting at Savage Hou&s;e, of improving his fortune.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fortune!&mdash;ay: and this morning he gave me his note for two hundred pounds, beg|ging me to get one of my guardians to lend money upon it&mdash;his excu&s;e was that his expen|ces exceeded his income, and by his uncle's marriage with Lady Sarah Savage, all his ex|pectations were ruined&mdash;Now, my life on't, this is all Sir George's doings&mdash;He has &s;tole into our cottage like the Arch-fiend into paradi&s;e, and I won't eat another apple while he &s;tays!</P>
<STAGE>(Throws away the apple &s;he is eating.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is Darnley then di&s;tre&s;&s;ed?&mdash;Oh Clara!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="6" REF="13">
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't be unhappy&mdash;I &s;hall apply to both my guardians; Sir Paul and Mr. Flu&s;h, they are now at Bath, and one way or other the Villa &s;hall flouri&s;h &s;till&mdash;Lord! I &s;hall have plenty of money when I come of age, and I'll throw it all into the &s;cale, and come and plant, &s;ow, and reap with you and your hu&s;band.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>What give up the gaieties of London, cou&s;in?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>London! ay: I hate it&mdash;I once pa&s;s'd a month there, but they hurried me &s;o from &s;ight to &s;ight, that in the bu&s;tle all places ap|pear'd alike&mdash;I &s;aw no difference&mdash;And, if you'll believe me, one morning after &s;eeing We&s;t|min&s;ter Hall in term time, they took me in|&s;ide Bedlam; and &s;o confus'd was I, that I didn't know the lawyers and their clients, from the keepers and their patients.</P>
<STAGE>(Signor Cygnet without).</STAGE>
<P>"Trompite, trompite tra!"</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(Singing an Italian air.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Who can this be?</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Signor</HI> CYGNET, <HI>&s;pying.</HI></STAGE>
<P>"Tra&mdash;tra&mdash;tra!"</P>
<STAGE>(Singing.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ble&s;s us!&mdash;What animal's this?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>He has mi&s;taken his way, I &s;uppo&s;e&mdash;Sir&mdash; <STAGE>(Signor don't regard her.)</STAGE> I beg pardon, Sir&mdash;but perhaps you don't know that this garden&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Signor.</SPEAKER>
<P>"Beviamo tutta tr&egrave;!"&mdash;ah, ha!&mdash; les Demoi&s;elles!&mdash;Ladies, &agrave; votre &s;ervice.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="7" REF="14">
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir!</P>
<STAGE>(Curt&s;eying.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Signor.</SPEAKER>
<P>I and the Honourable Mi&s;ter Savage arrive la&s;t night&mdash;ce Matin I take a my little valk&mdash;&s;ee your &s;mall Chateau, and am &s;o en|chant&eacute; w<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="2 letters">h the &s;pect&agrave;cle that&mdash;me voici!&mdash;I honour you with my fir&s;t vi&s;it&mdash;eh bien!&mdash;vat is your names?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>Our names!&mdash;rather we &s;hould a&s;k yours.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Signor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mine!&mdash;Diable!&mdash;do you not know me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;how &s;hould we?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Signor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Vat! not know I am Signor Cygnet&mdash; de fir&s;t Violin in Europe! de be&s;t compo&s;er in de whole world!&mdash;de hu&s;band of Signora Cygnet &mdash;de great &s;inger at de opera&mdash;de profe&s;&s;ional&mdash;de Abbey&mdash;de&mdash;Marbleu!&mdash;and am I not my&s;elf?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;I don't think you are your&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>And &s;o, Sir, you are on a vi&s;it at Mr. Savage's?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Signor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oui&mdash;in my vay to Bath I con|de&s;cend to pa&s;s a few days there&mdash;Lady Sarah Savage, &s;he love mu&s;ic, or pretend to love&mdash; vich is de &s;ame ting you know&mdash;they entertain me comme &ccedil;&acirc;&mdash;give me good dinners, and take ticketts for mine and my vife's concert&mdash;mais there be two tings I don't like.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>And what are they, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Signor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Vy Mi&s;ter Savage, he give me cold &s;uppers and &s;leep in the be&s;t bed him&s;elf&mdash;Now, begar!&mdash;I vill have hot &s;uppers and de be&s;t bed, or el&s;e I take a my fiddle and promenez&mdash;"Malbrouk s'en va, &amp;c." <STAGE>(Singing.)</STAGE>&mdash;De grand Duke&mdash;O! de grand Duke&mdash;he never u&s;e me thus&mdash;never&mdash;jamais!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="8" REF="15">
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>The Grand Duke!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Signor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oui&mdash;ven I was at Florence how you tink he treat me? accoutez&mdash;he quarrel with all his Mini&s;ters&mdash;all but one!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>And who was that one?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Signor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Me!&mdash;me he &s;hake by the hand and go to my vife's benefit to&ucirc;t le m&ecirc;me&mdash;de &s;ame as ever!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>&mdash;[To Mrs. Darnley.]</STAGE>
<P>Upon my word, mu&s;ic &s;eems &s;o important a &s;cience, that I think you had better let your little boy have &s;ome le&s;&s;ons&mdash;it is nece&s;&s;ary for his education&mdash;isn't it, Signor?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Signor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nece&s;&s;aire!&mdash;ma foi: 'tis de only education now-a-days&mdash;never mind vat you call Latin and Greek&mdash;put de fiddle in his lit|tle hand and let him &s;crape away! den he vill be great man&mdash;like me: and call for hot &s;up|per and be&s;t bed verever he go!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>What! &s;hall I give up making a par&s;on of him, Clary?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Signor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Par&s;on!&mdash;pif!&mdash;vat is de par&s;on to de mu&s;ician?&mdash;he ride his old white hor&s;e&mdash;preach away at four or five churches, and vat he get?&mdash;forty pounds a year&mdash;Eh bien! I and my vife ride in vis-a-vis&mdash;&s;ing only ven we like, and make five thou&s;and a year&mdash;ah ha! voila la difference!&mdash;Par&s;on!&mdash;begar! de blind fidler get more money!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>More &s;hame for the country then, where foreign arrogance is &s;o rewarded, and gentlemanly merit &s;o in&s;ulted&mdash;come Clara&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="9" REF="16"><HI>Re-enter Sir George</HI> GAUNTLET.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't be alarmed, Mrs. Darnley; but I and your hu&s;band have ju&s;t been pre&s;ent at an accident, that&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>An accident, &s;ir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes: Lady Sarah Savage, who is one of tho&s;e ladies call'd female phaetoneers, was driving four in hand acro&s;s the heath; the hor&s;es took fright, and ran away with her, when Darnley, with more gallantry than pru|dence, rode a-head of the unruly animals, and &s;topt them on the edge of a precipice.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Heaven be prais'd!&mdash;and where is the lady, &s;ir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>My friend is conducting her to the villa, where he begs you'll in&s;tantly join them.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>By all means&mdash;come&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>To Clara.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>Signor, won't you a&s;&s;i&s;t your friend?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Signor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Non&mdash;I am mu&s;ician, not phy&s;ician, and my head is &s;o full of de tune.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>So full of de vapour, he means&mdash;like the in&s;ide of his own violin&mdash;come cou&s;in&mdash;now isn't it a pity, that while we have butterflies and bullfinches in the garden, we &s;hould be tormented with coxcombs and fiddlers&mdash;in&s;ects, adieu</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exeunt</HI> Clara <HI>and Mrs.</HI> Darnley.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Signor, I rejoice to &s;ee you; you have often a&s;&s;i&s;ted me in my amours, and I now want your aid more than ever.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Signor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Eh bien!&mdash;my vife has a concert at Bath next week.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Has &s;he! then I'll give a dinner to &s;ome Somer&s;et&s;hire bumpkins, and force off
<PB N="10" REF="17">a &s;core or two of tickets&mdash;You &s;aw the lady I fir&s;t &s;poke to&mdash;&s;he has won my heart, and I have won her hu&s;band's.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Signor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dat is good&mdash;den if you make de di&s;cord between them&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, Sgnior: if I excite jealou&s;y! and this accident has &s;prung the mine&mdash;Lady Sarah Savage is already half in love with Darn|ley&mdash;She has invited him to Savage hou&s;e, and if he takes Mrs. Darnley along with him&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Signor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dey will be both out of tune for ever&mdash;ah ha! I go to Mr. Savage, toute&s;uite.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do&mdash;and increa&s;e Lady Sarah's love for Darnley&mdash;a&s;&s;i&s;t in all my &s;chemes; triumph I mu&s;t, and will; for I offer'd Mrs. Darnley my hand long before this hu&s;band won her heart.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Signor.</SPEAKER>
<P>I will be fir&s;t fiddle re&s;t a&s;&s;ur&egrave;&mdash;tenez; I vill compo&s;e two duettos&mdash;one between Lady Sarah Savage and de hu&s;band&mdash;de other be|tween you and de vife&mdash;all&ograve;ns. You no con|ceive the power of mu&s;ic, Sir George.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>I do, Signor&mdash;for as Shake&s;peare &s;ays: <Q>There's nought &s;o &s;tocki&s;h, hard and full of rage, but mu&s;ic for a time does change its nature.</Q></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Signor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Shake&s;peare! vat is dat Shake&s;peare? He never compo&s;e a &s;ingle tune, and dough at pre&s;ent he make a little noi&s;e, begar, you'll &s;oon find de fiddle and de bravura vill lay him on de &s;helf&mdash;now-a-days, &s;ound always get de better of &s;en&s;e, mon ami&mdash;Ah ha! venez! you no forget my vife's benefit.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exeunt.</STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="scene">
<PB N="11" REF="18">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE II.</HI>&mdash;A Room in&s;ide Mr. <HI>DARNLEY'S</HI> Villa, Prints, Books, Fowling Pieces, Fi&s;hing Tackle, <HI>&amp;c.</HI></HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Mrs.</HI> DARNLEY <HI>and</HI> CLARA.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well Clara: if Lady Sarah Savage be a picture of town-bred women of fa&s;hion, let me remain a plain &s;imple ru&s;tic all my life&mdash;Did you ever &s;ee any thing &s;o confi|dent&mdash;&s;o ma&s;culine&mdash;her brother too! "What you call impudence," &s;ays he, "we call ea&s;e."</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay: they're a precious pair; and yet in London they are both the Rage!&mdash;quite at the top of the beau monde&mdash;But, cou&s;in, they've order'd their carriages, and in&s;i&s;t on our going to Savage hou&s;e&mdash;Mercy on us! what's to become of two lambs among&s;t &s;uch a parcel of wolves?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>This is Sir George's &s;cheme: to delude Mr. Darnley from this tranquil &s;pot into fa&s;hionable life, is the fir&s;t &s;tep towards af|fecting his ba&s;e de&s;igns&mdash;He told Mr. Savage about your fortune too&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>I know it: and the vulgar man made downright love to me directly;&mdash;'faith-Coz. I believe Sir George wants to get me married, and you unmarried.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah Savage without.)</SPEAKER>
<P>Bring round the Phaeton, and d'ye hear&mdash;don't tighten the curbs&mdash;I'll whip and gallop them every inch of the road.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>"She'll whip and gallop them!" there now!&mdash;this is one of the modern breed of
<PB N="12" REF="19">fine ladies, who, in&s;tead of being feminine and tender, have the Rage for confidence and bold|ne&s;s&mdash;Look at her dre&s;s&mdash;&s;he's more like a man than a woman, and her language is as ma&s;cu|lin&egrave; as her manners.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Lady</HI> SARAH SAVAGE <HI>dre&s;&s;ed in a great coat, with a number of capes; a plain round beaver hat; a fur tippet and &s;a&s;h. Boot &s;hoes, a whip in her hand, and a riding habit, under great coal; two grooms enter with her.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>John, exerci&s;e the pointers, and the hounds&mdash;I &s;hall &s;hoot to-morrow, and hunt the next day.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Groom.</SPEAKER>
<P>Any thing el&s;e, madam?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;nothing&mdash;Oh yes: call at the taylor's and enquire for my fencing jacket&mdash;tell him I broke two foils in my la&s;t rencontre, and a&s;k him if any body ought to make a&s;&s;aults in a gown and petticoat?&mdash;Ah! my little dears&mdash;here <STAGE>(Seeing Mrs. Darnley and Clara, &s;he makes them pull off her great coat, which the groom takes.)</STAGE> Well! and how do ye do? Oh Wil|liam!&mdash;tell the recruiting &s;erjeant I mu&s;t learn the new military manoeuvres, and bid him bring the large&s;t fu&s;il in the regiment&mdash;there&mdash;go along&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Groom Exeunt.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I hope you have recover'd your fright, ma'am.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>Recover'd!&mdash;heh!&mdash;why, where's my deliverer!&mdash;my dear charming Mr. Darnley?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Madam!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>He is certainly the mo&s;t divine engaging creature&mdash;I mean to take him home
<PB N="13" REF="20">with me, and the Phaeton is waiting&mdash;&s;o call him, child&mdash; <STAGE>(to Clara.)</STAGE> call him directly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>Call:&mdash;whom, madam?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, Mr. Darnley, to be &s;ure; what does the girl &s;tare at?&mdash;did &s;he never &s;ee a per&s;on of quality before.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>Never&mdash;its the fir&s;t time, ma'am; and if this is the &s;pecimen, I hope it will be the la&s;t:&mdash;I'll call Mr. Darnley.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>I wi&s;h I was like you, my dear&mdash;I wi&s;h I was married&mdash;its &s;o comfortable&mdash;&s;o con|venient&mdash;heigho!&mdash;I &s;hall be &s;o glad when old Sir Paul is my &s;talking hor&s;e&mdash;my hu&s;band I mean&mdash;&s;han't you, Mrs.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Excu&s;e me, madam: when I reflect, that Sir Paul is Mr. Darnley's uncle, and by your union he is deprived of all his future fortune, you cannot blame me, if &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>Deprive my dear Darnley of his fortune!&mdash;&s;o it does&mdash;well!&mdash;that's va&s;tly droll!&mdash;but then it makes mine, which is the &s;ame thing you know&mdash;See!&mdash;here's my bear of a brother!&mdash;you've no idea what low, vulgar company he keeps?&mdash;nothing but Buffoons, Bow-&s;treet Officers, and Boxers!&mdash;and only conceive, my dear, me and my friends mixing in &s;uch horrid &s;ociety.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Surely Mr. Savage cannot wi&s;h&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>He does, ma'am: and only con|ceive I &s;ay my intimate acquaintance&mdash;people of the fir&s;t con&s;equence&mdash;&s;uch as Signor Cyg|net, the hu&s;band of the fine Soprano&mdash;Mon&s;ieur Puppitini, the inventor of the dear Fantoccini, and Count Spavin the greate&s;t of Hor&s;e Doctors&mdash;only imagine &s;uch pick'd com|pany
<PB N="14" REF="21">as this, mixing with my brother's low-liv'd wretched crew.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed, ma'am, people of rank ought to &s;et a better example.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter the Honourable Mr.</HI> SAVAGE.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>So Savage&mdash;&s;i&s;ter I mean&mdash;I lo&s;t ten pounds by your &s;illy accident&mdash;The moment I &s;aw the hor&s;es off, I &s;aid to my friends around me, ten pounds to five, the driver gets a tum|ble&mdash;"done!"&mdash;"it's a bett" &s;ays I&mdash;away flew the racers,&mdash;&s;nap went the reins&mdash;five to four in my &s;avour!&mdash;when plague on't! the Squire rode acro&s;s, &s;topt the carriage&mdash;you &s;av'd your neck, and I&mdash;lo&s;t my wager.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>You brute: did you ever hear your brother, Lord Savage, talk in this man|ner?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>My brother!&mdash;pough!&mdash;he's a gen|tleman to be &s;ure&mdash;proud, independent, and all in the grandee &s;tyle&mdash;but I!&mdash;I'm not like him&mdash;I'm a man of fa&s;hion&mdash;I'm not a gentleman.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;that you are not upon my honour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am the hero of my &s;ociety&mdash;he is the &s;lave of his&mdash;he keeps high company, ma'am <STAGE>(To Mrs. Darnley,)</STAGE> lives with judges, generals, and admirals&mdash;but does he ever encourage the arts and &s;ciences? does he ever &s;hake hands with men of genius? &s;uch as peace officers, tennis play'rs, and boxers&mdash;no, no&mdash;that was left for me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes: and though born to wealth and titles, there you &s;tand, that have been &s;ix times bottle holder at a boxing match!&mdash;vulgar &s;cience!&mdash;I hope Sir Paul don't under&s;tand it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="15" REF="22">
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;not now&mdash;but if he makes you his wife, it may be nece&s;&s;ary he &s;hould, learn,&mdash; I &s;ay, ma'am, that was a &s;traight one&mdash;wasn't it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed I don't know, &s;ir; &mdash;Wou'd Mr. Darnley were here!&mdash;I am unequal to their &s;ociety; but from the lit|tle I have learnt, I think one hour of dome&s;|tic life worth all this new unintelligible &s;cene.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hark'ye: <STAGE>(to Lady Sarah,)</STAGE> here's a letter from the old beau, Sir Paul&mdash;he is coming to Bath, and can only &s;tay one day with us, in his way; but as people of quality are not always people of quantity you know, he &s;han't &s;tir, till the marriage is effected&mdash;mum!&mdash;I'll keep him clo&s;e&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> DARNLEY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! &s;quire!&mdash;come Mrs. Darnley; <STAGE>(takes her by the hand.)</STAGE> I'll drive you and your pretty cou&s;in&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, I am unus'd to vi&s;iting; unfit&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>Non&s;en&s;e!&mdash;I never take an excu&s;e; when I a&s;k people to my hou&s;e, I make them go when I like&mdash;&s;tay while I like, and behave as I like&mdash;&s;o come along&mdash;&s;quire mind you don't &s;nap the reins; and d'ye hear; as my &s;i&s;ter is rather lame&mdash;only ju&s;t recover'd from the gout&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>The gout!&mdash;how dare you, &s;ir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>What!&mdash;do you deny it?&mdash;do you di&s;own having been our'd by a quack doctor, and returning him thanks in all the papers? <Q>Lady Sarah Savage informs Dr. Panacea, that his alagaronic anti&s;pa&s;modonic tincture, has entirely remov'd the gout from the extremi|ties,
<PB N="16" REF="23">and &s;he now hunts, &s;hoots, eats and drinks more freely than ever!</Q>&mdash;now isn't it a &s;hame, ma'am? between them, they plun|der both the patient and the phy&s;ician.&mdash;The quack cheats the doctor of his fee, and the woman robs the man of his gout.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit with Mrs.</HI> DARNLEY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Mr. Darnley!&mdash;I am &s;o glad you're going to Savage hou&s;e&mdash;'twill be &s;uch a relief&mdash;come&mdash;I'll appoint you my rural Cicis|beo&mdash;my guardian &s;hepherd&mdash;you &s;av'd my life, and I won't let you die for me, I am deter|min'd!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exeunt.</STAGE>
</DIV3>
<TRAILER>END OF ACT I.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="2" TYPE="act">
<PB N="17" REF="24">
<HEAD>ACT II.</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE I.</HI>&mdash;The Honourable Mr. <HI>SAVAGE'S</HI> Park and Garden&mdash;a Canal with a Ve&s;&s;el on it&mdash;a Bridge&mdash;a Temple &s;urrounded with Weeping Wil|lows&mdash;at the Wing a Portico and Steps leading to the Hou&s;e.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> DARNLEY <HI>and Sir</HI> GEORGE GAUNTLET <HI>from the Portico.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why now indeed you are an alter'd man?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am&mdash;I am&mdash;the wine&mdash;the &s;cene &mdash;the company&mdash;has &s;o tran&s;ported me, that I begin to think I'm not quite &s;ober, Sir George&mdash; I do indeed.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>No wonder at it&mdash;you've led the life of a reclu&s;e and every new &s;cene dazzles you &mdash;you are like a nun e&s;cap'd from a convent.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;more like a Friar in one&mdash;at lea&s;t if I may judge by my eating and drinking&mdash; But my friend&mdash;this is a glorious place, and I begin to think I've liv'd too long out of the world&mdash;coop'd up in a cottage&mdash;buried in a farm&mdash;What did I know of life and all its plea|&s;ures?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay: what indeed?&mdash;in town&mdash;and Savage-hou&s;e is the &s;ame thing you &s;ee; for they always bring London into the country with them &mdash;but Lady Sarah, Darnley&mdash;I &s;aw you at din|ner;&mdash;&s;he gave you &s;uch affectionate looks.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fie! fie Sir George&mdash;you forget&mdash; I am a married man.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>A married man!&mdash;what then!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="18" REF="25">
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why then I love my wife&mdash;I do&mdash; I tenderly love her&mdash;and when I chu&s;e to play the fool, let me expo&s;e my&s;elf, but not wound her for heaven's &s;ake!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Non&s;en&s;e!&mdash;you don't know Lady Sarah&mdash;&s;he is one of tho&s;e confident females, who won't let a man e&s;cape&mdash;who mark you for their prey&mdash;lure you into their talons; and, if you don't yield, will &s;o claw you.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>What! make me love her whether I will or not?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Certainly: but con&s;ider the ad|vantages of her friend&s;hip: fir&s;t &s;he can get you promotion in the army; &s;econdly, by gaining an a&s;cendancy over her, you may prevent her marrying your uncle; and thirdly, you can pro|vide for your family without injuring your ho|nour&mdash;there!&mdash;there's an opportunity!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's true; and if I thought&mdash; hark'ye; as we're alone, and you're my be&s;t of friends&mdash;I've got a letter from her! the Signor brought it me&mdash;here! <STAGE>(taking out a letter.)</STAGE>&mdash;She appoints me to meet her in her dre&s;&s;ing-room.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Bravo, Signor!&mdash; <STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE>&mdash;let's read. &mdash; <STAGE>(Reads the Letter.)</STAGE>&mdash; <Q>Lady Sarah Savage, having &s;omething particular to communicate to Mr. Darnley, begs to &s;ee him in her dre&s;&s;|ing-room in an hour's time.</Q>&mdash;Go by all means,&mdash;go, I in&s;i&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, if I can per&s;uade her not to mar|ry Sir Paul, or even get her to interfere with him &mdash;I'll go!&mdash;I'm fix'd&mdash;I'll write to her this in&s;tant. <Q>He that e&s;&s;ays no danger gains no prai&s;e!</Q></P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="19" REF="26"><HI>Enter the Honourable Mr.</HI> SAVAGE <HI>ha&s;tily.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>Joy! joy my lads! Sir Paul is arri|ved! and how do you think the old boy intro|duced him&s;elf to my porter?&mdash;"Tell your ma&s;|ter, &s;ays he, a young gentleman de&s;ires to &s;ee him."</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Young gentleman!&mdash;that's ex|cellent&mdash;he's at lea&s;t &s;eventy-two.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, you wrong him; he's only &s;e|venty&mdash;Sir Paul Perpetual&mdash;Old P. I mean; for that's his nick name you know&mdash;has been the ancient beau of the age the&s;e thirty years, and as his great grief is, that he never had a &s;on, he wants my con&s;ent to marry my &s;i&s;ter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>And do you mean to con&s;ent, &s;ir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>Certainly&mdash;I &s;ay <STAGE>(a&s;ide to Sir George)</STAGE> &mdash;I want his fortune to repair my own, and therefore he &s;han't leave the hou&s;e till the mar|riage is effected&mdash;you know my way.&mdash;I've given the hint to the &s;ervants.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter a Servant.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Servant.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir here's the young gentleman.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>Squire, take my place at the table&mdash; pu&s;h the wine about, and tell the jovial crew to prepare for quizzing&mdash;quizzing you rogue!&mdash; go <STAGE>(Darnley exit)</STAGE>&mdash;the licen&s;e is in my pocket, a par&s;on's in the hou&s;e, and if we can but con|fu&s;e the young gentleman, we'll marry him in a joke, and afterwards take his fortune in earne&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="20" REF="27"><HI>Enter</HI> SIR PAUL PERPETUAL, <HI>in a riding dre&s;s.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>"Be lively, bri&s;k and jolly!&mdash;lively, bri&s;k and jolly!" <STAGE>(&s;inging.)</STAGE> Ah, my boys!&mdash;here I am&mdash;as young and hearty&mdash;but I can't &s;tay; I mu&s;t be at Bath to-morrow.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>At Bath!&mdash;what to drink the wa|ters? to renovate before marriage, Sir Paul.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;upon my &s;oul there's no occa|&s;ion&mdash;though, at pre&s;ent, perhaps a little phy&s;ical advice wouldn't be much ami&s;s: for between our&s;elves, I've ju&s;t cut a tooth, and &s;uffer'd mo&s;t violently from the hooping cough! <STAGE>(They laugh)</STAGE> &mdash;Why what do you laugh at?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nothing&mdash;nothing&mdash;only we won|der'd how &s;uch a chicken as you could &s;truggle again&s;t a pair of &s;uch mortal di&s;orders!&mdash;but, &s;eriou&s;ly&mdash;what takes you to Bath?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>Such an event? I have trac'd a &s;on; a boy above twenty years of age! that's my fir&s;t rea&s;on&mdash;my &s;econd is&mdash;to &s;ee my grandfather.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your grandfather!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hark'ye&mdash;he &s;hall make &s;ettlements on my fir&s;t four children.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pray, Sir Paul&mdash;I beg your pardon though&mdash;what age may your grandfather be?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>Two hundred, if he's an hour! heh? an't I right, old P.?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>Old P.! there it is now!&mdash;here I &s;tand, that walk as much as any man&mdash;that ride as much as any man&mdash;that am every night at a concert, an opera, or a club&mdash;that &s;ing, dance, game or intrigue! and what's more, that have done all this for &s;ixty years!&mdash;and yet to be call'd
<PB N="21" REF="28">old P!&mdash;they &s;aid I never was a father&mdash;but I &s;hall &s;oon prove the great and glorious fact.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay! how will you prove it?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>How! why you've all heard of my little Nelly&mdash;poor girl! &s;he was jealous, and &s;he left me to marry a trade&s;man&mdash;a clerk at a lot|tery office, and three months after we parted &s;he was deliver'd of a boy&mdash;a fine boy! as like me as one Cupid is to another&mdash;a year after her marriage, &s;he died, and I can hear nothing of her hu&s;band; but let him &s;ay what he will, I'll &s;wear the boy was mine; I'll &s;wear it, becau&s;e I'm convinc'd I'm father to more children than one, Sir George.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very likely; but where did you learn all this?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>From Nelly's &s;i&s;ter; a month ago I accidentally met her at Tunbridge; &s;he had neither &s;een nor heard of the hu&s;band &s;ince her &s;i&s;ter's death, but &s;he remember'd the child went by his mother's name! its mine!&mdash;I'm &s;ure its mine! and <STAGE>(they laugh again.)</STAGE> I tell you what&mdash;you'd better be careful; for when you and other young &s;prigs of fa&s;hion &s;mile at me, jeer me, and call me the infirm old P.!&mdash;'gad! you little think you dogs, you are laughing at your own father perhaps! however, I've trac'd my boy to Bath, and whoever di&s;covers him &s;hall have the too be&s;t racers in my &s;tud.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>What fidget and fizgig? then I'll &s;eek for young P. my&s;elf&mdash;I'll find him&mdash;I'll&mdash; but hold&mdash;hold&mdash; <STAGE>(Stopping Sir Paul who is going)</STAGE> don't go yet&mdash;your nephew's in the hou&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>What Darnley?&mdash;zounds! then I won't &s;tay a moment&mdash;no&mdash;not even to &s;ee my dear Lady Sarah, who I'll marry if its only to
<PB N="22" REF="29">di&s;appoint that rural reprobate&mdash;that&mdash;I'm gone.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;you're not&mdash;I'll tell you a &s;ecret; you &s;hall &s;tay a week with me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>A week!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay: I've my rea&s;ons&mdash;&s;o don't think of &s;tirring; for your hor&s;es are turn'd out to gra&s;s&mdash;your &s;addles and bridles &s;nug in a hid|ing place, and all the gates double bar'd, in&s;ide and out.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>What the devil! make a pri&s;oner of me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>Non&s;en&s;e!&mdash;I only fore&s;tall your wi&s;hes:&mdash;I'm &s;ure you want &s;ome &s;oft di&s;cour&s;es with my &s;i&s;ter, and don't I know what my vi&s;i|tors like better than they do them&s;elves? don't I know you like getting drunk?&mdash;&s;o come; come in and drink!</P>
<STAGE>(Pulling him.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>I don't&mdash;I hate drinking; and death and fire! haven't I told you I want to find my &s;on&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(A&s;ide to Sir Paul.)</STAGE>
<P>Humour him; humour him, Sir Paul; or he'll refu&s;e you his &s;i&s;ter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay: give con&s;ent, or el&s;e&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>Or el&s;e I lo&s;e my wife I &s;uppo&s;e; when I'm in the country, don't I like always to live quiet, and keep early hours, and would you lock me in a hou&s;e where you never &s;ee the &s;un? where you go to bed ju&s;t before it ri&s;es, and get up the moment after it &s;ets?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>Will you give up the marriage, and let Darnley have his wi&s;h?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;I'll die fir&s;t&mdash;I'll&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then will you join the jolly crew and prove&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="23" REF="30">
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>That you have as much health, youth, and &s;pirits&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>As any choice &s;pirit&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Or young gentleman&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>In the whole world!&mdash;I'm rous'd! I'm fir'd! and to &s;hew I'm &s;ea&s;on'd! true Engli&s;h heart of Oak!&mdash;all&ocirc;ns!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Singing.)</STAGE>
<P>"Bring the fla&s;k! the mu&s;ic&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Singing.)</STAGE>
<P>"Joy &s;hall quickly find us&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>"Let us dance and laugh and &s;ing, and drive old care behind us!"</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exeunt at Portico.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Mrs.</HI> DARNLEY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Can this be the man&s;ion of ele|gance and ta&s;te? I meet with nothing but rude|ne&s;s and neglect!&mdash;I wi&s;h I could find Mr. Darn|ley!&mdash;I dare &s;ay, by this time, he is &s;icken'd of the &s;cene, and anxious as my&s;elf, to &s;ee his home again.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> DARNLEY <HI>from the Portico, half drunk, with Lady Sarah Savage's letter in his hand.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Speaking as he enters.)</STAGE>
<P>Fill away my boys!&mdash;fill!&mdash;fill!&mdash;while I like a faithful gal|lant!&mdash;gallant! hold, hold, friend Darnley. This letter is to benefit your intere&s;t, not &s;acrifice your honour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Heavens!&mdash;what do I &s;ee? Mr. Darnley!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Not regarding her.)</STAGE>
<P>Yes:&mdash;you do; you &s;ee Mr. Darnley.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="24" REF="31">
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why?&mdash;what's the matter with you!&mdash;what's that letter?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>This letter?&mdash;this is a love letter, my angel,&mdash;ha!&mdash;why it is!&mdash;it is my wife!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes: that wife who in the hour of di&s;&s;ipation you forget&mdash;can I believe it?&mdash;in a little hour can all our pa&s;t attachment&mdash;but why am I alarmed?&mdash;Fa&s;hion may dupe the wicked and the weak, but virtue &s;uch as his mu&s;t &s;corn its empty power.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Forget!&mdash;no never!&mdash;and now I look at you&mdash;I think I ought to be ma&s;&s;acred for having even for a moment neglected you&mdash;Oh Maria!&mdash;I have &s;uch news for you&mdash;Lady Sarah has been &s;o kind&mdash;&s;he has promi&s;ed to promote me&mdash;to befriend you&mdash;and in &s;hort &s;he has taken a liking to the whole family.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>And why, Harry?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why! ay: there's the rub! but don't be jealous, Maria&mdash;I entreat you, don't be jealous!&mdash;for by heaven, I love you!&mdash;I do &s;o ten|derly that if it were not for my promi&s;e, I could find in my heart to return home directly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnly.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do; let us begone&mdash;the place di&s;tracts me: and I fear this high company will corrupt you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>High company!&mdash;hang it:&mdash;if that's all you're afraid of, there's not much danger in this hou&s;e I fancy&mdash;but my letter&mdash;my word to Sir George&mdash;and con&s;ider our intere&s;t, Maria.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh no&mdash;con&s;ult our happine&s;s my love; and &s;urely there is none in this tumultu|ous &s;cene&mdash;we left all joy behind us, in our children and our cottage, Harry; and there alone we &s;hall recover it&mdash;come.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>She's right&mdash;the pretty prattler has rea&s;on on her &s;ide and who can di&s;obey&mdash; <STAGE><HI>(looks
<PB N="25" REF="32">without,)</HI></STAGE> ha!&mdash;Sir George and Lady Sarah in clo&s;e conver&s;ation!&mdash;they beckon me!&mdash;again!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why do you pau&s;e?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'm in for it&mdash;the die is ca&s;t!&mdash;Ma|ria!&mdash;excu&s;e me.</P>
<STAGE>(going from her.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>How! will you leave me, Mr. Darnley?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>What can I do?&mdash;'tis but for a &s;hort time.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mrs. Darnl<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">y.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You mu&s;t not.</P>
<STAGE>(Laying hold of him.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay: only for an hour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Letting him go and taking out her handkerchief.)</STAGE>
<P>&mdash;This is the fir&s;t time you ever us'd me thus.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>So it is&mdash;now what a pretty &s;coun|drel I am!&mdash;and this is fa&s;hionable life is it?&mdash;Oh fool! fool! to quit &s;ub&s;tantial peace for artificial plea&s;ure!&mdash;don't weep, Maria&mdash;I go for our mutual advantage&mdash;I go to make our chil|dren happy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then &s;tay with their mother&mdash;they never wi&s;h'd that we &s;hould part.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nor will we&mdash;we've liv'd &s;o long and happily together, that I would rather lo&s;e the little we have left, than hurt your quiet.&mdash; <STAGE>(Enter Sir George Gauntlet.)</STAGE> Sir George &s;tay with her&mdash;I'll &s;ee Lady Sarah, entreat her forgivene&s;s, and return in&s;tantly; for, oh my friend!&mdash;my heart drops blood for every tear &s;he &s;heds.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>P'&s;ha!&mdash;remember your intere&s;t&mdash;Lady Sarah will &s;oon reconcile your &s;cruples, and leave me to compo&s;e Mrs. Darnley&mdash;nay: take your opportunity&mdash;you mu&s;t keep the ap|pointment&mdash;I in&s;i&s;t&mdash;&s;o begone!&mdash; <STAGE>(Darnley exit.)</STAGE> What a fu&s;s here is about a man's leaving his
<PB N="26" REF="33">wife for an hour, when &s;o many worthy couple would be happy to part for ever.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir George, tell me, where is he gone? tell me, that I may fly and overtake him!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why! can't you gue&s;s?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, indeed, I cannot.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not that he is gone to Lady Sarah to keep an a&s;&s;ignation with her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>An a&s;&s;ignation.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>In her dre&s;&s;ing-room! at this very hour&mdash;the gay &s;cene has &s;o alter'd him, that you &s;ee he has left you to keep the appointment.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll not believe it!&mdash;he is above &s;uch ba&s;ene&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Won't you?&mdash;then I'll prove it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I defy you!&mdash;he knows the value of my heart too well to trifle with it; and I've known his &s;o long, that I'll not venture to &s;u&s;pect it&mdash;no&mdash;though his friend defames it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay then&mdash;you remember his hand-writing&mdash;here is his an&s;wer to the lady's letter&mdash;read.</P>
<STAGE>giving her the letter.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Looks over it.)</STAGE>
<P>Ha!&mdash;it is too plain&mdash;I am deceiv'd&mdash;de&s;erted.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>I was the bearer of that letter, and pre&s;erv'd it merely to &s;hew it you, I thought it the duty of a friend.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>And from the &s;ame duty, you advis'd him to write it.&mdash;Oh! I have known you long, Sir George&mdash;you are one of tho&s;e who find no happine&s;s but in marring that of others&mdash;who &s;educe the affections of the hu&s;band, the better to betray the honour of the wife! and when you've &s;poilt all &s;ocial and dome&s;tic peace, the
<PB N="27" REF="34">friend you laugh at, and the woman &s;corn!&mdash;I know you well!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear ma'am, how you mi&s;take!&mdash;I meant to oblige you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir&mdash;there is but one way&mdash;leave me&mdash;nay, I in&s;i&s;t&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hall obey.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I mu&s;t have &s;tronger proof be|fore I am convinc'd, and then ob&s;erve, Sir George, if his truth weakens, I'll add &s;trength to mine! my con&s;tancy and honour &s;hall be &s;o ex|emplary, that I will &s;hame him from his follies! make him repent: and when reclaim'd, be proud to &s;ay he is my own again!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exeunt.</STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE II.</HI>&mdash;An elegant Apartment leading to Lady <HI>SARAH'S</HI> Dre&s;&s;ing-Room&mdash;the Door in the Flat.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> CLARA.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes: yes: its all over the Hou&s;e&mdash;Sir George makes no &s;ecret of the a&s;&s;ignation, and I've no doubt but Darnley is now in that room waiting for Lady Sarah Savage&mdash;&s;he can't come at pre&s;ent&mdash;the &s;ervant &s;ays, &s;he's gone to the &s;tables to &s;ee the bea&s;ts unharne&s;s'd&mdash;faith! if &s;he'd go to her brother's party &s;he'd &s;ee that bu&s;ine&s;s already done!&mdash;however I'll pre|vent Darnley's expo&s;ing him&s;elf, and as he is certainly conceal'd in that room, I'll talk to him.&mdash;Dear!&mdash;here's my guardian again!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="28" REF="35"><HI>Enter Sir</HI> PAUL PERPETUAL, <HI>(ha&s;tily.)</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>So far, I'm &s;afe, my dear girl; you don't know what your poor guardian has &s;uf|fer'd in this high&mdash;no&mdash;this low-lif'd hou&s;e!&mdash;they forc'd me into a room full of buffoons, boxers, and blacklegs&mdash;made me drink a bowl of punch, and I'd as &s;oon drink &s;o much poi&s;on&mdash;then winking and nodding they began whi&s;pering pretty loudly&mdash;"&s;moke the old prig!&mdash;damme, quiz him!"</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>Quiz him!&mdash;what's that, Guardy?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, with our young men of qua|lity, quizzing is a &s;ub&s;titute for wit, my dear; &s;o one man challeng'd me to play on the violin, and when I ro&s;e to move my elbows, another whip'd the chair from under me; a &s;econd put hot coals into my pocket, &s;o when I felt for my hankerchief, I burnt my fingers; a third tried to cut off my tail, but that a&s;&s;a&s;&s;in I pur&s;ued, when unluckily in running after him, they had tied a &s;tring acro&s;s the &s;tairs, and I pitch'd headforemo&s;t into a <HI>barrel</HI> of water, they had placed for the purpo&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed, its quite terrible, Gaurdy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then they &s;hew'd me a licen&s;e; brought me a fat par&s;on, and &s;aid, if I'd in|&s;tantly be married, they'd let me go to find my &s;on&mdash;if not, I &s;hould be lock'd in, and have plenty of it&mdash;now here's ho&s;pitality!&mdash;but they've over&s;hot the mark; and if I get out of their doors, I'll not only break off the match, but promi&s;e to befriend Darnley.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>What! di&s;appoint Lady Sarah, and relieve my poor di&s;tre&s;&s;ed friend&mdash;then I'll get you out
<PB N="29" REF="36">of the hou&s;e&mdash;I will, if I'm quizz'd to death for it&mdash;You &s;ee that door&mdash;if he meets Darnley, he'll at lea&s;t interrupt the a&s;&s;ignation.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>Secure my e&s;cape&mdash;only get me out of this den of &s;avages, and, if I don't befriend Darnley, may I never live to &s;ee old age. Where does that door lead to?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>I fancy to Lady Sarah's dre&s;&s;ing room; for it is full of half boots, hor&s;e great coats, mi|litary &s;a&s;hes, helmet caps, and amazonian jack|ets! and this is your only way to e&s;cape&mdash;enter that room.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>Put on one of Lady Sarah Savage's great coats, tie one of her &s;a&s;hes round your wai&s;t&mdash;throw a fur tippet about your neck, and with a whip in your hand, and her driv|ing hat on your head&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>I under&s;tand&mdash;the &s;ervants will take me for their mi&s;tre&s;s, and open the gates; Oh! you dear girl! <STAGE>(ki&s;&s;es her.)</STAGE>&mdash;I'll about it in&s;tantly&mdash; <STAGE>(opens the door in flat.)</STAGE> I &s;ay, Clara, the hounds below are unkennel'd; they have &s;tarted me for game, and after keeping them at bay, by &s;ou&s;ing in a flood of water, I take to cover; that is, I put on Lady Sarah Savage's cloathes to avoid pa&s;&s;ing for a wild bea&s;t; mum!</P>
<STAGE>(enters the room.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>If he does but get out of the hou&s;e, the marriage is broken off and Darnley made happy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah Savage</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(without.)</STAGE>
<P>I'm at home to nobody but Mr. Darnley.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Going to the door.)</STAGE>
<P>We're undone, ruin'd; &s;tay where you are; here's Lady Sarah.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(putting his head out)</STAGE>
<P>&mdash;The devil!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="30" REF="37">
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hu&s;h! lock your&s;elf in, and don't &s;tir till I tap at the door, or &s;top&mdash;&s;top&mdash;le&s;t &s;he or &s;omebody el&s;e &s;hould tap, don't open it till I give you a &s;ignal&mdash;let me &s;ee; what &s;hall be the watchword? Oh, "quizzing," you won't for|get "quizzing," Guardy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;I &s;hall remember it the&s;e fifty years; &s;o when I hear the word "quizzing," out I come, and&mdash;&s;oftly&mdash;here &s;he is</P>
<STAGE>(&s;hutting him&s;elf in.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Lady</HI> SARAH, <HI>with pocket-book and tickets in her hand.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Speaking as &s;he enters.)</STAGE>
<P>Tell my dear Signor, I &s;hall get rid of all the&s;e benefit tickets; heh! <STAGE>(taking out her &s;pying gla&s;s.)</STAGE>&mdash;what young creature's this?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>How d'ye do again ma'am?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>Again! you're va&s;tly forward child; I never &s;aw you before.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>No ma'am! that's very &s;trange; you &s;aw me this morning at Mr. Darnley's, and in|vited me to your hou&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, ay: now I recollect; you mu&s;t excu&s;e me; we people of rank are &s;o very ab&s;ent; we're extremely intimate with a per&s;on in the morning, and don't know them at night; well! I'm va&s;tly glad to &s;ee you; but you mu&s;tn't &s;tay here, I'm engaged child.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;han't intrude, ma'am&mdash;good day.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>Adieu! &s;top&mdash;&s;top&mdash;I forgot; give me two guineas.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>Two guineas, ma'am!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes: for the&s;e tickets; they're for the Signor's wife's benefit at Bath next Mon|day,
<PB N="31" REF="38">the whole town will be there&mdash;nay, I &s;hall at|tend&mdash;I'd make you take more, but as you'll have to pay card money bye and bye, it would be a&s;king you to one's hou&s;e ab&s;olutely to make a bargain of you! <STAGE>(Clara gives the two guineas.)</STAGE> there&mdash;you may go.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>A bargain indeed! and a bad one too: for if I was mean enough to make money by my gue&s;ts, would I lay it out on foreigners who loll in carriages? no&mdash;not while &s;o many of our gallant &s;oldiers and &s;ailors have only wooden limbs to &s;tand on! <STAGE>(half a&s;ide.)</STAGE> I am gone, ma'am, <STAGE>(curt&s;eying.)</STAGE> and now may Darnley get out of the &s;crape&mdash;Sir Paul get out of the hou&s;e&mdash;and &s;he and her brother knock their &s;tupid heads to|gether.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;uppo&s;e this &s;illy creature has interrupted the charming Mr. Darnley, and he has &s;tept into my dre&s;&s;ing room&mdash; <STAGE>(goes to the door and finds it fa&s;ten'd.)</STAGE>&mdash;lock'd in&s;ide&mdash;it mu&s;t be &s;o&mdash; <STAGE>(li&s;tens)</STAGE>&mdash;I declare I hear him moving; <STAGE>(&s;he li&s;tens again)</STAGE>&mdash;he &s;ighs!&mdash;poor man! <STAGE>(&s;he &s;peaks loudly.)</STAGE>&mdash;don't be dejected, my dear &s;ir; when I'm married to that old tottering beau, Sir Paul, I'll think of nothing but you. So come, Mr. Darnley, <STAGE>(Enter Mrs. Darnley,)</STAGE> come my &s;weet Mr. Darnley.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Can it be po&s;&s;ible?&mdash;then all's confirm'd madam, when I am convinced that my hu&s;band&mdash;that Mr. Darnley has been de|coyed into that room.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(&s;pying at her.)</STAGE>
<P>Ble&s;s me!&mdash;its Mrs. Darnley!&mdash;this is a little aukward&mdash;how|ever I'll &s;oon talk her out of it, <STAGE>(a&s;ide.)</STAGE> Don't be unea&s;y, my dear&mdash;the&s;e fa&s;hionable intrigues are
<PB N="32" REF="39">very harmle&s;s, I'll a&s;&s;ure you, and if you had had my free and liberal education&mdash;but poor thing! I &s;uppo&s;e you were &s;ent to &s;chool for in&s;truction.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mr. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>To &s;chool! as certainly ma'am&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>There it is then: for what could you learn! only to &s;ing well enough to &s;poil conver&s;ation&mdash;to play on the harp&s;ichord, &s;o as to give papa, mama, and the whole family an afternoon's nap&mdash;to dance &s;o aukwardly as to be always out of tune and place; and to &s;peak ju&s;t French enough, to make you forget Engli&s;h; this is a boarding &s;chool education&mdash;But I my dear&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hear me, madam! when I fir&s;t &s;aw you, I was the happie&s;t of women&mdash;I had a hu&s;band who lov'd and honour'd me&mdash;who doat|ed on his children, and knew no plea&s;ure but in his family! and now how &s;evere is the rever&s;e! you have robb'd me of that trea&s;ure, &s;educ'd it from my heart, and I return to a melancholy home, without a friend for my own di&s;tre&s;&s;es, or a father for my children!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>And how can I help it?&mdash;didn't I mean to do you both a &s;ervice by introducing you to the great world?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Great world!&mdash;there again, madam!&mdash;when I enter'd this hou&s;e, I expected from the exalted rank of its owner to have been &s;urrounded with kindne&s;s, elegance, and ho&s;pita|lity!&mdash;but I find that high birth doesn't create high breeding, nor am I, becau&s;e humbly born, le&s;s likely to &s;et a poli&s;h'd example than your&s;elf&mdash;Oh Darnley! why will you not come forth and &s;ave your once lov'd wife from agonies too great to bear.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="33" REF="40"><HI>Enter Mr.</HI> SAVAGE.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>So Savage&mdash;here's a pretty &s;tory buzz'd about!&mdash;they &s;ay that Darnley, the country '&s;quire, is lock'd up in your dre&s;&s;ing-room! if this is true you Jezabel&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>Scandalous brute!&mdash;but I don't wonder at it, you've had &s;uch a low vulgar educa|tion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>I had an education!&mdash;well that's more than ever you had!&mdash;but look'ye, Mi&s;s, no time mu&s;t be lo&s;t; for if Sir Paul di&s;covers your intriguing, he'll break off the marriage, and we are ruin'd&mdash;yes; ruined madam! <STAGE>(to Mrs. Darnley,)</STAGE> you and your infamous hu&s;band will make your own plots and marr mine&mdash;&s;o I'll unkennel him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hold, &s;ir&mdash;indeed he is not to blame&mdash;he was betray'd into that room.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>Betray'd!&mdash;nay, then I mu&s;t con|fe&s;s, brother, that Mr. Darnley is there; I dare &s;ay he conceal'd him&s;elf on purpo&s;e to expo&s;e me to Sir Paul&mdash;nay, I am &s;ure of it now.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage,</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(looking thro' the key-hole.)</STAGE>
<P>I &s;ee him through the key-hole&mdash;the ra&s;cal's in di&s;gui&s;e! <STAGE>(enter two &s;ervants.)</STAGE> John call up the club&mdash;un|loo&s;e the hounds&mdash;tell the whole hou&s;e to pre|pare for quizzing&mdash;quizzing, you rogue.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Sir</HI> PAUL <HI>dre&s;s'd in Lady</HI> SAVAGE'S <HI>Great Coat, &amp;c. opens the door, endeavours to e&s;cape, but meeting Mr.</HI> SAVAGE <HI>retires again directly.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage</SPEAKER>
<P>&mdash;John, open the back-door, and &s;hew the di&s;guis'd gentleman out of the hou&s;e directly&mdash;go&mdash;and as for you Mrs. Darnley&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="34" REF="41">DARNLEY <HI>enters, and Mrs.</HI> DARNLEY, <HI>Lady</HI> SARAH, <HI>and</HI> SAVAGE, <HI>&s;tand a&s;toni&s;hed.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>Confu&s;ion!&mdash;Darnley!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is he then innocent?&mdash;Oh Har|ry!</P>
<STAGE>(Embracing him.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>Amazing! why, who was that wretch in my coat, hat, and tippet!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>No le&s;s a gentleman than Sir Paul Perpetual&mdash;Clara told me the whole &s;tory&mdash;he put on that di&s;gui&s;e to avoid the &s;nares that were laid for him, and he has ere this left the hou&s;e, determined to break off an union, that would have undone me and my family&mdash;lady Sarah, I entreat your pardon; but here <STAGE>(taking Mrs. Darnley by the hand,)</STAGE> here is my apology.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Re-enter Servant.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Serv.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, I have &s;hewn the di&s;guis'd gentle|man down &s;tairs.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>Go to the devil with you.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Kicks the &s;ervant off.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>Brother!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>Si&s;ter!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>We are the fools that are out|witted.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes: we've turn'd out the wrong man&mdash;but let's pur&s;ue and overtake him in&s;tant|ly; come,&mdash;'&s;quire, I in&s;i&s;t you leave my hou&s;e directly, and as to you Mi&s;s&mdash;if I catch the young gentleman, I'll have &s;ome &s;port, I'm de|termined&mdash;I'll turn you both loo&s;e among&s;t the hounds below, and the Club &s;hall decide, whe|ther
<PB N="35" REF="42">ther old P. isn't the prettie&s;t looking female of the two!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit with Lady Sarah.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I re&s;olved, Maria, to meet any cen|&s;ure, rather than give a pang to &s;uch a heart as yours; but let us be gone&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay: let us return to our villa, nor ever wander more.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;not yet Maria.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not yet!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;I have a plan to execute&mdash;Sir George, my be&s;t of friends, has invited us both to his aunt's hou&s;e at Bath, and is now waiting without to conduct us.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do not go! let me entreat you; do not&mdash;I have a thou&s;and fears.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, nay: he will introduce us to friends, who can render us e&s;&s;ential &s;ervice; come&mdash;come&mdash;indulge me&mdash;the &s;ociety will be plea&s;ant, and unlike this ill-bred &s;cene&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well! if it mu&s;t be &s;o&mdash;Ah, Har|ry! I have now pa&s;s'd hours in the humble and exalted &s;cenes of life, and I find that good breed|ing is confin'd to no rank or &s;ituation! it con&s;i&s;ts in good &s;en&s;e, and good humour, and I believe we may &s;ee as large a &s;hare of it under the roof of the cottage, as in the &s;plendid man&s;ions of the great!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exeunt.</STAGE>
</DIV3>
<TRAILER>END OF ACT II.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="3" TYPE="act">
<PB N="36" REF="43">
<HEAD>ACT III.</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE I.</HI>&mdash;A &s;uperb room in <HI>FLUSH'S</HI> hou&s;e; hand&s;ome &s;ideboard of Plate&mdash;Pictures in elegant Frames&mdash;gilded chairs&mdash;two &s;ervants in fine live|ries, putting &s;ilver coffee pot, tea urn, &amp;c. on the table for breakfa&s;t, a third &s;ervant &s;hewing in <HI>READY.</HI></HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> READY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ready.</SPEAKER>
<P>Tell your ma&s;ter, his agent de&s;ires to &s;ee him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Servant.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, Mr. Flu&s;h is hardly dre&s;t yet.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ready.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not up!&mdash;why it's two o'clock.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Servant.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very likely, &s;ir&mdash;my ma&s;ter &s;eldom ri&s;es &s;ooner&mdash;be&s;ides he gave a grand &s;upper la&s;t night; all the fir&s;t people in Bath were pre&s;ent, &s;ir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ready.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well! well! tell him Mr. Ready is here: <STAGE>(Servant exit.)</STAGE> now isn't it amazing that a man who was only twelve years ago clerk to a lottery-office-keeper in London, &s;hould be &s;o rich, and &s;o vi&s;ited, and how has he done all this? how, but by the modern my&s;tery of money lending!&mdash;by opening a &s;hop in the city for li|nens, gauzes; and mu&s;lins&mdash;by keeping a fine hou&s;e near Bond &s;treet, and another in Bath. His &s;on manages in London, and I here, while he by not appearing, is every where noticed and re&s;pected.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(without.)</STAGE>
<P>James! Thomas! tell the cook to &s;end a plan of my dinner.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="37" REF="44">
<SPEAKER>Ready.</SPEAKER>
<P>He's &s;uch an epicure! and he, who formerly could &s;carcely get nece&s;&s;aries, is now not &s;atisfied with luxuries.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>FLUSH <HI>enters with two &s;ervants.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(&s;its.)</STAGE>
<P>Ha! Ready! how d'ye do, Ready?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ready.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir!</P>
<STAGE>(bowing.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sit down, Ready&mdash;&s;it down. <STAGE>(Ready &s;its.)</STAGE> well! how go on money matters?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ready.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have alter'd the adverti&s;ement as you de&s;ir'd, and in&s;erted it in the Bath and Bri&s;tol papers.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Read it&mdash;read it. <STAGE>(Takes up a pine ap|ple on the breakfa&s;t table)</STAGE> You &s;coundrels! <STAGE>(to the &s;ervants.)</STAGE> is this a pine apple for a gentleman? buy a larger; buy one if it co&s;ts ten pounds; I can afford it&mdash;read, Ready, read.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ready.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Reading a news-paper.)</STAGE>
<P><Q>Money mat|ters!&mdash;the nobility, gentry, ladies of fa&s;hion, officers of rank, bankers, &amp;c. may be &s;ecretly accommodated with money to any amount, on per&s;onal &s;ecurity only, by applying to P. O. Holly Street, Bath&mdash;No. 93.</Q></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Excellent! well! does the trap fill! have you caught any birds?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ready.</SPEAKER>
<P>Plenty; plenty of pigeons already; <STAGE>(Takes out his pocket-book.)</STAGE> here, here's a note for five hundred&mdash;left by a da&s;hing young par&s;on&mdash;I think it's good.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Looking at it.)</STAGE>
<P>It is&mdash;treat him well; give him value; I can afford it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ready.</SPEAKER>
<P>Value! but in what manner, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(ri&s;ing.)</STAGE>
<P>Oh! pay him in the old way, Ready; fir&s;t, give him my draft at a week for
<PB N="38" REF="45">thirty guineas, then offer him damag'd linen and mu&s;lin to the amount of one hundred and twenty, and bid him call again in a fortnight&mdash;you have his note all the time you know.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ready.</SPEAKER>
<P>Certainly, &s;ir; and when he calls&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Give him a bad bill for one hundred and fifty, and pay him the odd hundred in trifles; &s;uch as pa&s;te buckles, gilt bracelets, We&s;tphalia hams, painted prints, neats tongues, and Stilton chee&s;es&mdash;&s;o &s;hake hands, and have done with Ma&s;ter Par&s;on.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ready.</SPEAKER>
<P>But not with the bill, &s;ir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;my bankers di&s;count it, and pay it away, till pa&s;&s;ing through different hands, &s;omebody gives value for it at la&s;t, and then the glorious work begins&mdash;then comes the hero into combat! an attorney is employ'd! an attorney, my boy! action is brought upon action! decla|ration filed upon declaration! till the drawer, acceptor, and indor&s;ers all get into the King's Bench&mdash;the King's Bench&mdash;no&mdash;I beg pardon; the high money-lenders, and low attornies, have &s;o fill'd it, with their dupes, that there isn't room there&mdash;the hou&s;e overflows! &s;o Newgate, Newgate is the &s;hop!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter a Servant.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Servant.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here's your &s;on! ju&s;t arriv'd from London!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Shew him in.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit &s;ervant.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ready.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'm told, &s;ir, Mr. Gingham is quite another man, &s;ince I &s;aw him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, yes, you knew his cur&s;t, ingenu|ous, candid di&s;po&s;ition; he learnt it in the coun|try, the dog would &s;peak the truth, and his &s;im|plicity
<PB N="39" REF="46">&s;o injur'd our trade, that I threatened to turn him out of doors; but he has reform'd Ready! the boy has the good &s;en&s;e to tell a lie now, and I've &s;ent for him to witne&s;s his ble&s;&s;ed reformation.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ready.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, &s;ir, your &s;on always &s;poke his mind too freely&mdash;in &s;hort, Mr. Gingham was too hone&s;t for his profe&s;&s;ion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>He was; however he has given me his word, never to &s;peak what comes uppermo&s;t, and he is now what he ought to be; a regular, &s;o|lemn, je&s;uitical&mdash;in &s;hort&mdash;he's a very promi&s;ing young man.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> GINGHAM.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, your hand&mdash;Ready yours, well! here I am&mdash;quite converted&mdash;like father, like &s;on&mdash;tell a lie without blu&s;hing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here&mdash;I told you &s;o&mdash;ay, ay, I knew the boy would come to &s;omething good at la&s;t&mdash;&s;o my dear boy you've left off telling the truth&mdash;&s;peaking your mind.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mum! clo&s;e as the cabinet&mdash;keep you in my eye&mdash;put on your face, and do it &s;o punctually, you wouldn't know young P. O. from your&s;elf&mdash; <STAGE>(Looking about the room,)</STAGE> zounds! what a fine hou&s;e you've got! how its furni&s;h'd! what plate! what pictures!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>The re&s;ult of trade and hone&s;t indu&s;try, Frank&mdash;yes&mdash;its pretty furniture isn't it?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pretty furniture! it's &s;o hand&s;ome, that except your&s;elf, cur&s;e me, if I &s;ee a &s;habby bit in the room!&mdash;nay, nay, upon my &s;oul, I didn't allude to you; I meant Ready.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="40" REF="47">
<SPEAKER>Ready.</SPEAKER>
<P>He's at his old tricks I &s;ee&mdash;as candid as ever.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Plague on't! I could &s;ooner bite off my tongue, than &s;top its &s;peaking what I think! nay, &s;ir, now pray.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, well, I excu&s;e you this once; I, a &s;habby bit! however we &s;hall &s;oon &s;ee&mdash;how goes on the &s;hop in London?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>The &s;hop!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, the &s;hop in the city that you've the care of&mdash;the linens&mdash;the&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh ay: now I recollect; why very well upon the whole, I believe, &s;ir&mdash;very well&mdash;only between our&s;elves; I'm afraid it won't la&s;t; I think we and our tricks &s;hall be found out&mdash;you under&s;tand&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Found out! '&s;blood, &s;irrah&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Softly &s;ir&mdash;&s;oftly&mdash;don't put your&s;elf in a pa&s;&s;ion, and lay the blame on me; don't charge me with our ruin, for every body knew my opinion long ago; didn't they, Ready? I told it to a thou&s;and people&mdash;&s;ays I, "&s;wind|ling will never thrive, and I and my poor fa|ther &s;hall get duck'd at la&s;t!"</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>You did! did you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>That I did, &s;ir; and I'll prove I &s;aid &s;o&mdash;the other night I &s;lept at the we&s;t end, and two friends&mdash;di&s;tre&s;s'd old officers in the army&mdash;brought their notes to be di&s;counted&mdash;&s;ays I, <Q>Gentlemen, it won't do&mdash;you'll get little ca&s;h, but a quantity of trumpery non&s;en&s;e, &s;uch as hams, chee&s;es, prints, linens, and other ve|getables!</Q> &s;aid they; <Q>we know that&mdash;we know you and your father are two infernal &s;harpers, but a guinea now is worth ten a month hence&mdash;&s;o give us the money.</Q></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="41" REF="48">
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well: and you took their note, didn't you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, I didn't&mdash;I gave them the ca&s;h, &s;hook the two old &s;oldiers by the hand, and &s;aid I was tir'd of &s;uch d&mdash;d &s;windling prac|tices.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ready.</SPEAKER>
<P>This is &s;ad work, Mr. Gingham you'll never be at the top of your profe&s;&s;ion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>The top!&mdash;Oh! what the pillory? no&mdash;I leave that to you, Ready!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Was there ever &s;uch a &s;coundrel?&mdash;but we'll hear more, <STAGE>(a&s;ide.)</STAGE>&mdash;So, you &s;leep at the we&s;t end of the town, do you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Always&mdash;its vulgar to be in the city of an evening; be&s;ides I like to walk in Ken&s;ington-gardens in the morning&mdash;You know Ken&s;ington-gardens, father&mdash;the place where there's &s;uch a mixture of green leaves and brown powder&mdash;of blue violets and yellow &s;hoes; and where there's &s;uch a croud, that to get air and exerci&s;e you &s;tand a chance of broken bones and &s;uffocation!&mdash;Well!&mdash;there I &s;trut away, my boys&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>You do&mdash;do you?&mdash;I can hardly keep my hands off the ra&s;cal&mdash;So then I &s;uppo&s;e, the moment my back was turn'd, you never thought of bu&s;ine&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Bu&s;ine&s;s!&mdash;no never&mdash;Did I, Ready? I recollected my father play'd the &s;ame game before me; that when he was clerk at the lottery-of|fice, at billiards all the morning, and at hazard all the evening&mdash;therefore, &s;ays I, where's the diffe|rence?&mdash;none! but that he had the policy to conceal his tricks, and I the folly to &s;hew mine&mdash;heh! I'm right&mdash;an't I, Ready?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>You villain!&mdash;is this your reformation? not even conceal your own faults, much more
<PB N="42" REF="49">mine. Expo&s;e my character, neglect my trade, and &s;trut away in Ken&s;ington-gardens! I have done with you from the country you came, and to the country you &s;hall return&mdash;Speak the truth, indeed! zounds! &s;irrah, what has truth to do with money lending!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Here Ready exit.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> CLARA SEDLEY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Guardy&mdash;I'm ju&s;t come to Bath with Mr. and Mrs. Darnley&mdash;we are all on a vi&s;it at Sir George Gauntlet's, and&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(&s;eeing Gingham, &s;he &s;tops.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Its only my &s;on, Clara&mdash;a &s;imple fooli&s;h young man.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(bowing to her.)</STAGE>
<P>More knave than fool, upon my honour, ma'am.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>The gentleman don't prai&s;e him&s;elf I &s;ee, Mr. Flu&s;h.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, ma'am&mdash;nor do I know any bo|dy that will prai&s;e me&mdash;unle&s;s my father indeed.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Silence, &s;ir!&mdash;well: but about the ru|ral pair, my dear ward; do you know I have a great regard for Mr. and Mrs. Darnley.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>Have you? I'm va&s;tly glad of that for your joint guardian, Sir Paul, is &s;o employ'd in &s;eeking for his lo&s;t child, that he has forgot his promi&s;e to a&s;&s;i&s;t Darnley; therefore I want you to do him a favour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>A favour!&mdash;he may command me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>The ca&s;e is this&mdash;his increa&s;e of family has &s;o enlarg'd his expences, that he has thoughts of returning to the army&mdash;Sir George has pro|mi&s;ed to procure him a company, but Mrs. Darnley, not chu&s;ing he &s;hould owe his promo|tion to him, wi&s;hes he &s;hould purcha&s;e; now,
<PB N="43" REF="50">Guardy, if you would lend him two hundred pounds.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Two hundred pounds, child!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, two hundred pounds, father!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Who bid you &s;peak, &s;ir?&mdash;Why, Clara, in money matters there is an etiquette.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>True: but this is your friend.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>So it is, ma'am: the man he has a great regard for.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>And when you con&s;ider the charms of Mrs. Darnley, and the wants of her children&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>He can't refu&s;e, ma'am&mdash;indeed he don't intend it&mdash;and therefore as I &s;ee he means to grant the favour, I'll &s;ave him the trouble of putting his hand in his pocket&mdash;Here, ma'am! <STAGE>(taking out bank notes)</STAGE> here are two bank notes of a hundred each&mdash;they belong to Mr. Flu&s;h&mdash;now they belong to Mr. Darnley&mdash; <STAGE>(Flu&s;h gets in his way and prevents Clara's taking them.)</STAGE>&mdash;he begs you'll give them to his friend&mdash;and pre&s;ent his compliments&mdash;and &s;ay, he'll double the &s;um.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Stand off&mdash;&s;tand off&mdash;or by heavens I'll&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Offering Clara the notes acro&s;s his fa|ther)</STAGE>
<P>Double the &s;um, whenever call'd upon, ma'am.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hold your tongue, or I'll knock it down your throat, &s;irrah.&mdash;I &s;ay, Clara, in the the way of bu&s;ine&s;s, I've no objection to do Mr. Darnley a &s;ervice; that is, if I can make a pro|fit by it&mdash;fir&s;t, he &s;hould &s;end me his note.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here it is, &s;ir.</P>
<STAGE>(Giving it to Flu&s;h.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's right&mdash;now we can proceed&mdash;here, &s;ir&mdash; <STAGE>(Giving the note to Gingham,)</STAGE> take the note to my agent, and tell him to give Mr. Darnley thirty pounds&mdash;I can afford it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="44" REF="51">
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>This is too bad&mdash;take in his own friend, and a man with a family, <STAGE>(a&s;ide.)</STAGE> Sir,&mdash;a word if you plea&s;e&mdash;I told you, we were all blown upon&mdash;now, here's an opportunity for retrieving our reputation&mdash;lend him the two hundred pounds&mdash;prove, for once, we can behave like gentlemen, and hark'ye&mdash;we &s;han't reach the top of the profe&s;&s;ion.</P>
<STAGE>(putting up his neckcloth.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>This is beyond bearing&mdash;quit the room directly&mdash;'sdeath!&mdash;leave my hou&s;e, &s;ir&mdash;be|gone!&mdash;I di&s;inherit you&mdash;I&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lord!&mdash;why &s;o angry, guardian?&mdash;I'm &s;ure he is a good young man, and as warm in his heart&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Warm in his heart!&mdash;non&s;en&s;e!&mdash;will he be warm in the funds? no&mdash;never&mdash;while he is &s;o candid&mdash;&s;o&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not while he is candid, &s;ir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;do you think I made my fortune by candour or openne&s;s; an&s;wer me, &s;ir&mdash;did I ever get a &s;hilling by &s;peaking the truth&mdash; &s;peak!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(In a melancholy voice.)</STAGE>
<P>No, &s;ir, I never &s;aid you did&mdash;I know the contrary, &s;ir; madam, I'm of a communicative di&s;po&s;ition, I own; but there are many &s;ecrets of my father's I never blabb'd.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Are there, &s;ir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, that there are, &s;ir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>I don't recollect them.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't you? Why, now, did I ever mention, &s;ir, that you got the&s;e pictures by &s;ue|ing out execution? That you got that plate, by its being pawn'd to you for half its value; that you intrigue with a female money-lender; and that the la&s;t time you were made a bankrupt,
<PB N="45" REF="52">you went to get your certificate &s;igned in a new vis-a-vis? did I, or will I ever mention the&s;e things?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Begone, &s;ir&mdash;I'll never &s;ee you more&mdash; Yet, &s;tay&mdash;you have papers in your po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion &mdash;meet me in an hour's time at my agent's, &s;ir, &mdash;at Mr. Ready's.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Forgive me this once, father&mdash;I'll never let the cat out any more.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, &s;ir, I never will forgive you&mdash; I am engaged, &s;ir, and you know we great men are &s;elect in our company.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, if it mu&s;t be &s;o&mdash;farewell, father! the world is all before me, and what trade to follow, heaven only knows. Good bye, madam!&mdash;your &s;ex will never befriend me, be|cau&s;e I can't keep a &s;ecret, you &s;ee.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>I will befriend you, &s;ir; for while there is &s;o much deception and hypocri&s;y in the world, it would indeed be unju&s;t, not to ap|prove &s;uch frankne&s;s and hone&s;ty. Guardy, let me intercede for him; I'll an&s;wer for his con|duct.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye; and if ever I mention duck|ing or &s;windling again.&mdash;There! you &s;ee he's fix'd, ma'am.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>At pre&s;ent he is, and therefore leave him, perhaps by the time you meet him at the agent's I &s;hall have talked him into good humour. Adieu! depend on't, I &s;han't forget your gene|rous intentions.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nor &s;hall I, yours; and if fortune &s;miles on me, I'll prove that I de&s;erve your kindne&s;s&mdash;If ever my father pardons&mdash;but I &s;ee he's more and more angry, &s;o I take my leave. May every ble&s;&s;ing attend you&mdash;may you meet with a heart as liberal as your own&mdash;May your
<PB N="46" REF="53">cou&s;ins' di&s;tre&s;&s;es vani&s;h&mdash;may your guardian once more value a &s;on, who can't help &s;peaking the truth for the &s;oul of him.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>Upon my word he's a charming man! and pardon him you mu&s;t, Guardy, if its only to plea&s;e me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;I'm determined.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter a Servant.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Servant.</SPEAKER>
<P>The dinner's ready.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, Clara, you &s;hall dine with me; I want to talk to you, and if I cou'd &s;ee my joint Guardian, Sir Paul&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>I met him at your door&mdash;he's only ju&s;t gone by.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ju&s;t gone by! that's a mi&s;take; for the old beau has been gone by the&s;e thirty years: however, come in&mdash;come, and eat and drink what you like. Call for burgundy, champagne, or tokay&mdash;Ay, call for tokay at a guinea a pint; I can afford it, my dear Ward, I can afford it.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exeunt.</STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="scene">
<PB N="47" REF="54">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE II.</HI>&mdash;The Cre&s;cent and the &s;urrounding country.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Lady</HI> SARAH SAVAGE, <HI>and Sir</HI> GEORGE GAUNTLET.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir George, I own my weakne&s;s: the proud, the haughty lady Sarah is humbled; Darnley has en&s;nared my heart, and one way or other, I mu&s;t in&s;ure his pity&mdash;Heigho! you are his friend, Sir George.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>You &s;ee I am; and that he e&s;teems me more than ever, is evident from his bringing Mrs. Darnley to my hou&s;e&mdash;did you mind his orders to her?&mdash;take an airing my dear with Sir George in his phaeton! it will rai&s;e your &s;pirits, my love!&mdash;Ha! ha! he ab&s;olutely throws her into my arms.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes; but &s;he ab&s;olutely contrives to get out of them again.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>She does; and therefore, there is no way but the one I mentioned&mdash;we mu&s;t make Darnley jealous.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>True:&mdash;I'll tell him that you love his wife.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, nay, not me&mdash;fix on &s;ome|body el&s;e&mdash;we'll &s;oon find an object, and then by convincing him of her fal&s;ehood, he naturally turns his thoughts to another woman; which is you, you know&mdash;and &s;he wanting a protector, con&s;equently flies to another man, which is me, you know we'll add the Signor to the confede|racy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="48" REF="55">
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>You're a &s;ad wretch&mdash;a &s;ad wretch indeed, Sir George, to impo&s;e on a friend, who places &s;uch confidence&mdash;&s;uch&mdash;I won't hear you&mdash;po&s;itively I won't hear you&mdash;only ob&s;erve, if I don't win the cruel Darnley's affections, I'll drive my Phaeton down a precipice in reality; I will, or with the bayonet of my fu&s;il, pierce my too tender heart, and expire at his feet.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter the honourable Mr.</HI> SAVAGE <HI>ha&s;tily.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>So Sarah&mdash;I and Sir Paul have had &s;uch an adventure!&mdash;though we quarrel'd la&s;t night, we made it up to day; for I never think alike two hours together&mdash;Do you, &s;i&s;ter?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>Never: but when I think of you brother, then I think more than I &s;ay, I a&s;&s;ure you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>No; you &s;ay more than you think, I a&s;&s;ure you&mdash;but would you believe it? The old boy has &s;een his &s;on,&mdash;we trac'd him from the &s;tage coach he came in, to the pump room, from the pump room, to the billiard room&mdash;there Sir Paul &s;aw him playing with the marker, and when he heard the young man's name, he fainted; actually fainted in my arms.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>What, in a fit! poor old man! well! if you'll believe me, Sir George, I never &s;aw a per&s;on in a fit in all my life.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>Long before he recover'd, the young man was gone&mdash;the bird was flown&mdash;for the &s;tanders by, all blacklegs began laying betts on Sir Paul's recovery, and tho&s;e who were again&s;t him, wouldn't let water be thrown in his face.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="49" REF="56">
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>Inhuman wretches!&mdash;they ought to have &s;ous'd him to death: but pray, brother, who is this child? where does he come from? what's the &s;tory?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why&mdash;about twenty years ago, Sir Paul's lady quarrell'd with him at Tunbridge, and married a citizen&mdash;Four months after the mar|riage &s;he had a &s;on, which the citizen brought up as his own, and Sir Paul now &s;wears the boy was his&mdash;'gad! it will be curious; for the child will have two fathers.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>Curious! not at all&mdash;but why &s;hould you meddle?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>Becau&s;e it &s;ecures me the two be&s;t racers in his &s;tud&mdash;Fidget and Fizgig; and what's better, becau&s;e it &s;till &s;ecures us Sir Paul's fortune: for though he won't marry you him|&s;elf, he intends his &s;on &s;hould; and, if I could but once more &s;ee the young man&mdash;I know he goes by his mother's name&mdash; <STAGE>(Looking out)</STAGE> heh! its him! there he is again!&mdash;get out of the way; don't interrupt&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;I have too great a regard for Sir Paul's property to interrupt any plan for &s;ecuring it; be&s;ides, Sir George and I have bu|&s;ine&s;s&mdash;come&mdash;I &s;ay brother, tell the old gentle|man to be careful, and in his eagerne&s;s bid him not claim another man's child in&s;tead of his own!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit with Sir</HI> George.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>Where can Sir Paul be loitering? he &s;aid he'd follow me&mdash;mum!</P>
<STAGE>Stands a&s;ide.</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="50" REF="57"><HI>Enter</HI> GINGHAM.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! what a whirligig world is this? I that was brought up to lend money; mu&s;t now try to borrow it: but where? who'll tru&s;t a wan|dering linen-draper! who'll tru&s;t the notorious young P. O.? however, Iv'e got my equivalent; I can &s;peak my mind now&mdash;no longer need I &s;mother my thoughts, and be ready to bur&s;t: no longer have an itching on my tongue, and be ready to bite it in two&mdash;no, no, I may open now. The &s;weet lady &s;ends me word my father is inex|orable, but hopes &s;he &s;hall &s;oon &s;ee me again; heigho! I hope &s;o too; when I think of her, my heart feels &s;uch queer &s;en&s;ations&mdash;I have it: &s;he has taken le&s;&s;ons of my father, and &s;windled me out of my affections; but then my poverty&mdash; I can never indulge even a hope.&mdash; <STAGE>(Sees Mr. Savage.)</STAGE>&mdash;Ha! here's the friend of the queer old gentleman, who fainted in the billiard room.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(advancing pompou&s;ly.)</STAGE>
<P>Sir, the honour|able Henry Savage has the plea&s;ure&mdash;the feli|city&mdash;What are you&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>the honourable?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay: why didn't you know it?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>No: nor never &s;hould if you hadn't told me&mdash;ha! ha! ha! ha!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! ha! ha! you're a droll dog! 'gad! you &s;hall come to my hou&s;e, and pa&s;s a week with me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Faith! a year with all my &s;oul! I've nothing to do with my&s;elf; I've left off trade; haven't change for &s;ixpence in the world,
<PB N="51" REF="58">and &s;o my little right honourable&mdash;I'll honour you with my company.</P>
<STAGE>[Shaking him by the hand.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hu&s;h! if you want money don't own it: we great people are clo&s;e&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>I know it; oeconomical too!&mdash;you live cheap.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>What! people of fa&s;hion live cheap?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>To be &s;ure; you don't pay; and if that i&s;n't living cheap, the devil's in't!&mdash;ha! here's the fainting gentleman again!&mdash;who the deuce is he?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>I fancy you'll find him a pretty near relation of yours&mdash;at lea&s;t, if you were born at Tunbridge, and your mother's name was Ging|ham.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>It was; that's the name of her, and of the town.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>Say you &s;o?&mdash; <STAGE>(Enter Sir Paul Perpe|tual,)</STAGE>&mdash;The racers are mine, Sir Paul!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay: my whole &s;tud&mdash;any thing: every thing! only let me have another peep at my dear boy!&mdash;only let me prove to po&s;terity!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>There he is!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>Where!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>There! there is your &s;on! who was born at Tunbridge&mdash;who&s;e mother's name was Gingham, and who is now without a &s;hilling in his pocket, or a friend in the world&mdash;joy! joy! old boy! you've got a young P. at la&s;t!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>Stand off! let me come at him; come to thy father's arms!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>My father!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay: thy real father! who has a for|tune to be&s;tow on thee, and health, youth, and &s;pirits to &s;hare in all thy plea&s;ures&mdash;The dog has my right eye to a T.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="52" REF="59">
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(To Mr. Savage.)</STAGE>
<P>Pray does your friend bite in his fits?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide to Gingham.)</STAGE>
<P>Hark'ye&mdash;its Sir Paul Perpetual! better known by the name of old P.&mdash;he has an immen&s;e property.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Has he?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes: and if its certain you are his &s;on, he'll give you every farthing of it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! if that's the ca&s;e&mdash;if he has an immen&s;e property&mdash;let me &s;ee who dare deny it? Sir, your ble&s;&s;ing!&mdash; <STAGE>(kneeling.)</STAGE>&mdash;I always &s;aid I wasn't my father's own child.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ri&s;e my boy! my darling! and tell us how the citizen educated you!&mdash;The turn of my no&s;e exactly!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>I've done with linens, gauzes, and mu&s;lins now!&mdash;let the &s;hop and all its &s;windling go to the bottom&mdash;I'm the &s;on of Sir Paul Perpetual, better known by the name of old P. I'm not a trade&s;man &mdash;.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>Trade&s;man!&mdash;zounds!&mdash;my &s;on brought up in a &s;hop! &mdash; how it freezes my warm blood!&mdash;look'ye, my boy&mdash;two things I mu&s;t re|que&s;t of you&mdash;never to talk about trade, or men|tion your former father's name.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Never&mdash;I'll never mention his name becau&s;e I de&s;pi&s;e it; but as to trade, what's bred in the bone, you know father &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well&mdash;well&mdash;come to Mr. Savage's hou&s;e; there we'll introduce you to your in|tended wi&s;e&mdash;Mi&s;s Savage will &s;oon break you of talking about trade, or the city&mdash;&s;o come along.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Savage.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay: pray give up the city&mdash;the rich rogues have no ta&s;te for us men of wit and ge|nius&mdash;they e&s;timate every thing by property,
<PB N="53" REF="60">and if the great Ben Jon&s;on&mdash;nay, if the great Big Ben were alive, is there one citizen would give the poor dogs a dinner?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;you're right there; in the ci|ty a man that has no money, has no wit&mdash;the &s;malle&s;t bank note is more entertaining than the wittie&s;t manu&s;cript; and talk of Ben Jon&s;on's name for jokes&mdash;damme, Abraham Newland beats him hollow! isn't it true, my boy?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>As true, as that you beat my other father hollow&mdash;come&mdash;henceforth, no money lending tricks for me. But young P. O. &s;hall &s;tick to gay old P.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exeunt.</STAGE>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="4" TYPE="act">
<PB N="54" REF="61">
<HEAD>ACT IV.</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE I.</HI>&mdash;A Drawing-Room in Mr. <HI>SAVAGE'S</HI> Hou&s;e at Bath.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Sir</HI> GEORGE GAUNTLET <HI>and Signor</HI> CYG|NET.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Bravo! Signor bravi&s;&s;imo!&mdash;and &s;o Lady Sarah Savage has actually per&s;uaded Darnley, that his wife loves another man?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Signor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Si&mdash;at fir&s;t he no believe&mdash;but Lady Sarah lay it down with &s;uch cour&acirc;ge&mdash;her oaths were &s;o &s;uperbe, and mine &s;o magnifique, that 'at la&s;t he accompany us with tears&mdash;pauvre Mi&s;ter Darnley!&mdash;Ah! ha!&mdash;you no forget my vife's concert.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>And who did you &s;ay Mrs. Darn|ley was attached to?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Signor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Attendez&mdash;Sir Paul&mdash;what you call&mdash;old P.&mdash;he has found one child&mdash;eh bien!&mdash;the enfant was at the comedie, and &s;aw Madame Darnley and her 'cou&s;in maltrait&eacute; by &s;ome qu'on appelle bobbies&mdash;villains who fight de duels, and interrupt de mu&s;ic&mdash;Vell! de child relieve de ladies, conduct them home&mdash;&s;up, and dough all de time he make love to Mad'moi&s;elle Clara&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yet, Lady Sarah Savage fixes on him for Mrs. Darnley's gallant&mdash;excellent! and if this &s;cheme fails, I under&s;tand &s;he has another&mdash;there is Mr. Flu&s;h&mdash;a &s;ort of money agent.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Signor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Je connois&mdash;je connois&mdash;he make a you poor, by lending you ca&s;h.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="55" REF="62">
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>This Mr. Flu&s;h has got Darnley's note for two hundred pounds&mdash;now he can't pay it; and therefore if Lady Sarah Savage buys it up&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Signor.</SPEAKER>
<P>Je comprehende&mdash;&s;he &s;ay, give me my heart, or pay me my money&mdash;ah ha!&mdash;I &s;ee you will be the fir&s;t fiddle your&s;elf;&mdash; <STAGE>(looking out.)</STAGE> le voici!&mdash;here is Mr. Flu&s;h!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;it's Sir Paul and the &s;on you &s;poke of&mdash;good day Signor&mdash;and if you &s;ee Darnley, tell him I'm out of town.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Signor</SPEAKER>
<P>I vill! &mdash; ecoutez&mdash;I no like to meet this Sir Paul&mdash;ven he a&s;k me to his hou&s;e, he always &s;ing him&s;elf&mdash;toujours&mdash;if he has de cold&mdash;de &s;ore throat&mdash;il chante! and begar: he &s;ing as well with the hoar&s;ene&s;s, as without&mdash;bon-jour, Sir George&mdash;bon-jour&mdash; <STAGE>(going, recollects and turns back.)</STAGE> Ah ha!&mdash;you no forget my vife's concert?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Darnley, jealous of his wife! and &s;he under my own roof!&mdash;now, if I can per&s;uade her to retaliate&mdash;here's her &s;uppo&s;ed gallant.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Sir</HI> PAUL <HI>and</HI> GINGHAM, <HI>elegantly dre&s;&s;ed.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>I tell you, father, Clara Sedley is the girl of my heart!&mdash;your ward is the girl for young P.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>Non&s;en&s;e!&mdash;haven't I made you a gentleman&mdash;&s;tuck a &s;word by your &s;ide?&mdash;haven't I brought you here to addre&s;s Lady Sarah Sa|vage?&mdash;ha! Sir George!&mdash;now mind <STAGE>(to Ging|ham)</STAGE> and conceal your low education&mdash;not a word about trade or the warehou&s;e; for I mean to put you into the army, and I've told every
<PB N="56" REF="63">body you've been on your travels.&mdash;Sir George!&mdash;my &s;on!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(bowing,)</STAGE>
<P>Sir, I'm very proud of the honour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir!&mdash;I'm very proud of&mdash; <STAGE>(bowing up to him, and &s;pying at his chitterlin)</STAGE>&mdash;right India mu&s;lin, by all that's&mdash;mum!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>You've been a great traveller, &s;ir,&mdash;much abroad?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Abroad!&mdash;yes, &s;ir&mdash;I was &s;eldom at home&mdash;generally at the We&s;t End, for between our&s;elves, though I was brought up to trade, I always de&s;pis'd the warehou&s;e&mdash;always&mdash;p&s;haw!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(taking him a&s;ide)</STAGE>
<P>Zounds!&mdash;mind what you're at&mdash;con&s;ider, if you talk as my &s;on, about linens and the warehou&s;e, they'll take your father for a trade&s;man; they'll &s;ay I'm a haberda&s;her, knighted on a city addre&s;s!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>A haberda&s;her!&mdash;that's a good one, a very good one&mdash;upon my &s;oul; Sir George, my father is'nt &s;uch a fool, as you take him for&mdash;no&mdash;that he isn't&mdash;are you, father?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah Savage.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(without.)</STAGE>
<P>When Mr. Flu&s;h comes, &s;hew him up &s;tairs.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here's your intended wife, &s;ir&mdash;'gad! I hope it will be a match, for Lady Sarah is &s;o anxious for a hu&s;band, that in the scramble, &s;he might &s;eize me at la&s;t&mdash;come, Sir Paul&mdash;let's leave the happy pair together.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now, remember what I told you&mdash;Lady Sarah is the e&s;&s;ence of fa&s;hion and good breeding; and if you want to poli&s;h, and rub off the city-ru&s;t, imitate her&mdash;copy her elegant manner.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay: &s;he's the rage!&mdash;and, if he wants to &s;ecure her affections, bid him imitate
<PB N="57" REF="64">his father, Sir Paul&mdash;copy you, and he mu&s;t &s;ucceed with the women.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, that he mu&s;t, Sir George&mdash;there's not a girl at Newmarket, not a dancer at the opera, or a &s;inger at the ancient concert, but adores me&mdash;they treat me with the &s;ame re|&s;pect they would a father&mdash;they &s;ay I'm &s;o quiet&mdash;&s;o inoffen&s;ive&mdash;&s;o harmle&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Harmle&s;s! do they &s;ay you're harm|le&s;s, father?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, harmle&s;s, and under that idea, I've done more mi&s;chief, then any ten danger|ous men in Europe&mdash;So copy her manners, and &s;ucce&s;s to you, my boy!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exit with Sir George.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Bravo! the&s;e are fine times, Ma&s;|ter Gingham,&mdash;but will they la&s;t?&mdash;is there no trick play'd, or to be play'd thee?&mdash;Sir Paul I'm told has a way of di&s;gui&s;ing him&s;elf in women's cloathes, &s;urely this is'nt another ma&s;|querading affair&mdash;Ah! here's &s;pou&s;e!&mdash;now to imitate her fa&s;hionable manners.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Lady</HI> SARAH SAVAGE.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>Marry him, I will: becau&s;e in the fir&s;t place, there's a &s;carcity of hu&s;bands; and in the next, being his wife, &s;ecures Sir Paul's fortune, and makes Darnley for ever in my pow'r&mdash;be&s;ides, I can draw the youth into all my &s;chemes&mdash;hem!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hem! <STAGE>(imitating her.)</STAGE> If this is a woman of fa&s;hion, the breed is grown pretty bold I think.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>I mu&s;t &s;hew him my &s;pirit&mdash;ter|rify him before marriage, in order to tame
<PB N="58" REF="65">him after. <STAGE>(Going towards him wriggling her head.)</STAGE> Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Going towards her wriggling his head.)</STAGE>
<P>Ma'am.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>Give me a chair!</P>
<STAGE>(Staring full in his face.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>A chair, ma'am?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, a chair, &s;ir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Staring full in her face.)</STAGE>
<P>E&s;&s;ence of breeding!&mdash;&s;he's the e&s;&s;ence of bra&s;s! <STAGE>(brings her a chair.)</STAGE> A chair, ma'am!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Staring vacantly.)</STAGE>
<P>He little knows what a life I &s;hall lead him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Shews alarm.)</STAGE>
<P>Heh!&mdash;a chair, ma'am!&mdash;here's a chair, I &s;ay&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(loudly.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, I forgot&mdash;I am really &s;o ab|&s;ent&mdash; <STAGE>(&s;its down)</STAGE> he! he! he!</P>
<STAGE>(&s;pying in his face.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(&s;itting down.)</STAGE>
<P>Are you really!&mdash;he! he! he!&mdash;I &s;hould like to&mdash; <STAGE>(mimicking)</STAGE> imitate her manners! hang me if I dare&mdash;&s;he has &s;et me all in a tremble&mdash;pheugh!</P>
<STAGE>(Puffing him&s;elf with his hat, and drawing his chair from her.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>Look up, my hero! <STAGE>(&s;lapping him.)</STAGE> You can't think how I rejoice at your be|ing de&s;igned for the army. I'm of a military, mar|tial turn my&s;elf, and &s;hall &s;erve every campaign with you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>You &s;erve campaigns!&mdash;I wi&s;h I was out of the room&mdash;pheugh!</P>
<STAGE>(a&s;ide.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hall make an excellent &s;ol|dier&mdash;a dauntle&s;s warrior! and if you talk of little unfledg'd fluttering en&s;igns, look at me&mdash;look!&mdash; <STAGE>(&s;haking him)</STAGE> march!&mdash;wheel about!&mdash;left!&mdash;make ready!&mdash;pre&s;ent!&mdash;fire!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="59" REF="66">
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Looking fir&s;t at her feet, then at her head.)</STAGE>
<P>It is&mdash;it is an impo&s;tor!&mdash;ugh!</P>
<STAGE>(whi&s;tles.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>Shan't I make a warlike appear|ance! animate one army, and intimidate ano|ther? re&s;tore the name of amazon&mdash;revive the age of chivalry, and if there are fools that threaten, and cowards that dread an inva&s;ion; Oh! how the thought fires me!&mdash; <STAGE>(ri&s;es,)</STAGE>&mdash;give me a few champions like my&s;elf, and we'll &s;tand on our white cliffs, and &s;care away whole na|tions.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Damme, it's another man in wo|man's cloathes! don't agitate your&s;elf&mdash;be com|pos'd&mdash; <STAGE>(to her as &s;he walks about.)</STAGE> what would I give to be &s;nug behind the counter?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am no timid helple&s;s woman; I can &s;hoot&mdash;I can fence&mdash;flouri&s;h a &s;word, or fire off a mu&s;ket!&mdash;penetrate your &s;word arm at the fir&s;t thru&s;t, or lodge a bullet in your fore|head at forty yards.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Keep cool&mdash;my hero keep cool! Oh! it's a clear ca&s;e&mdash;it's a man, and here am I to rub off the ru&s;t, by being run through the bo|dy! &s;it down my fine fellow! &s;it down.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fine fellow!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, I &s;ee how it is&mdash;Sir Paul has adopted me out of joke, and you are to make mince meat of me for my vanity!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, what is all this! <STAGE>(&s;miling.)</STAGE> mince meat!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>He &s;miles! then the joke's at an end, and they don't mean to hurt me! give me your hand&mdash;you comical dog, give me your hand.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>Comical dog! what do you mean? explain.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="60" REF="67">
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Explain! nay: that's too bad&mdash;do you think I don't know you my jolly boy?&mdash;do you think I can't &s;ee you are a gentleman?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>What! I a gentleman?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, and a brave one too!&mdash;why I &s;u&s;pected you at fir&s;t &s;ight!&mdash;I &s;aw there was nothing feminine about you, and then when I looked you full in the face, "pooh," &s;ays I, this can never be a woman!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not a woman!&mdash;have I &s;tudied modern fa&s;hions? exceeded all the pre&s;ent race of high &s;pirited women! only to be mi&s;taken for&mdash;Oh Lord! I never wept before in all my life&mdash;but this&mdash;Oh, I &s;hall faint&mdash;Oh! Oh!</P>
<STAGE>(Sits in a chair weeping.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> FLUSH.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>My ra&s;cal of a &s;on has gone off with all my papers&mdash;Darnley's note among&s;t the num|ber&mdash;and though Lady Sarah would give twice the value for it, I cannot find him&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(advancing to him.)</STAGE>
<P>Hu&s;h! not &s;o loud father&mdash;he'll flouri&s;h a &s;word&mdash;fire off a mu&s;ket!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>He!&mdash;who!&mdash;but how came you here, &s;ir? in this di&s;gui&s;e too!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Phoo!&mdash;it isn't me that's di&s;guis'd; a word&mdash; <STAGE>(whi&s;pers to him)</STAGE>&mdash;there!</P>
<STAGE>(pointing to Lady Sarah Savage.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>What! that lady!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>No; that comical dog&mdash;I'm &s;ure of it&mdash;mum!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! ha! ha!&mdash;you blockhead! why it's Lady Sarah Savage! &s;he's rather ma&s;culine to be
<PB N="61" REF="68">&s;ure: but Lord help you&mdash;&s;he and I are old friends.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>What! you know her? do you!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Know her!&mdash;why I'll take my oath &s;he's a woman.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>He'll take his oath!&mdash;Oh then I &s;ee my error&mdash;&s;he's on the pav&eacute;, di&s;carded; and they want to palm her on me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fool!&mdash;would you make more blun|ders! can't you tell a women of fa&s;hion from a&mdash;.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;there it is, &s;ir,&mdash;if women of fa&s;hion will talk and dre&s;s like women of ano|ther de&s;cription, who the devil can tell one from the other! and, if likewi&s;e they will hunt, &s;hoot, and fence, and prefer ma&s;&ccedil;uline a&s;&s;urance, to feminine diffidence, is it amazing, that a gentle|man &s;hould confound the &s;exes? however, I'm glad it's not a man.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come&mdash;come&mdash;without further en|quiry, give me Darnley's note; the one Clara brought; the comical dog there, as you call her, is in love with Darnley, and wants to hold the bill as a rod over his head: I &s;hall only a&s;k her one hundred pounds premium for it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Taking the note out of his pocket book.)</STAGE>
<P>Only a hundred premium! heh!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>No; I can afford it: and &s;he, by arre&s;t|ing him, can make her own terms&mdash;you under|&s;tand!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Perfectly; &s;o I'll &s;hew her the note, and make peace&mdash; <STAGE>(goes towards Mi&s;s Savage, who is &s;till &s;itting.)</STAGE>&mdash;madam&mdash;lady.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>P&s;haw! don't come near me, brute.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="62" REF="69">
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am convinc'd of my mi&s;take, ma'am&mdash;this gentleman will take his oath on the &s;ubject, and therefore&mdash;in hopes of making amends&mdash;here is a note, my lady; a note of Mr. Darnley's for two hundred pounds.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>What did you &s;ay, &s;ir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>A note of Mr. Darnley's, ma'am!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Looking at it.)</STAGE>
<P>So it is; &s;ign'd with his own dear hand&mdash; <STAGE>(ri&s;es)</STAGE>&mdash;well, now I look at you again, &s;ir, I'm quite a&s;ham'd of our &s;illy mi&s;|under&s;tanding&mdash;I am indeed&mdash;he! he! perhaps it was my fault&mdash;nay&mdash;I dare &s;ay it was&mdash;and &s;o, that's Mr. Darnley's note, is it?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>It is, and now I recollect, wasn't the lady I conducted from the play, his wife?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>It was&mdash;but entre nous&mdash;what's the price of that fooli&s;h bit of paper?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Only three hundred pounds! one hun|dred for the premium, and two for the princi|pal.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here is the money then.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Putting his hand on hers.)</STAGE>
<P>Softly; keep the principal, becau&s;e you'll both want it, and as to the note, I'll keep that, le&s;t &s;omebody el&s;e &s;hould want it! <STAGE>(putting it in his pocket,)</STAGE> you brought me up to the trade, and if I haven't learnt a trick or two, Mr. Flu&s;h, it's no fault of yours.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>What! would you turn &s;windler, you ra&s;cal!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, this is a new mode of get|ting money.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;not &s;o very new&mdash;is it Mr. Flu&s;h?&mdash;however, as the wife is the only per&s;on that ought to have a pow'r over the hu&s;band,
<PB N="63" REF="70">I'll e'en go in&s;tantly to Mrs. Darnley, and give it her.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> DARNLEY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley,</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(fiercely.)</STAGE>
<P>What, &s;ir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>A note for two hundred pounds, &s;ir,&mdash;have you any objections? never mind the lo&s;s of the premium, Mr. Flu&s;h&mdash;you can afford it, you know&mdash;adieu!&mdash;Mr. Bluff, <STAGE>(To Darnley, who is frowning,)</STAGE> your &s;ervant&mdash;it wouldn't do&mdash;you you comical dog, it wouldn't do!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(Shewing Lady Sarah Savage the note, and exit.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(To Lady Sarah Savage.)</STAGE>
<P>'Sdeath!&mdash;this is the very man you told me of.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, now can you want further proof of his attachment to your wife?&mdash;I'll leave it to any body?&mdash;isn't it evident, Mr. Flu&s;h?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>His giving her two hundred pounds is a &s;trong circum&s;tance to be &s;ure&mdash;but then, when I recollect the money is mine, and not his&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>What then, &s;ir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why then, I think, the lady ought to be in love with me, and not him, &s;ir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll &s;et out for London, and never &s;ee her more&mdash;yet no&mdash;I'll be &s;atisfied&mdash;I'll know the wor&s;t!&mdash;I'll in&s;tantly pur&s;ue this new found idol of her heart, and if I catch him in her pre&s;ence&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>Kill him&mdash;for a wretch, who can't di&s;tingui&s;h the human &s;pecies, isn't fit to live&mdash;come&mdash;I'll go with you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>So will I&mdash;but pray don't kill him, till I've got my papers.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="64" REF="71">
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, don't fret about it, Mr. Darnley&mdash;you &s;hall return with me to Savage-hou&s;e&mdash;come&mdash;never think of going to Lon|don at this time of year&mdash;it's &s;o thin&mdash;all the great hou&s;es are lock'd up, and there's no mak|ing a fa&s;hionable party; is there, Mr. Flu&s;h?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your pardon, ma'am&mdash;I and my attor|ney can always collect a fa&s;hionable party, and if the great hou&s;es are lock'd up, why there are great people in lock-up-hou&s;es, &s;o don't be afraid of finding good company, Mr. Darnley!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(Exeunt.)</STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE II.</HI>&mdash;A library in Sir George Gauntlet's hou&s;e.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Sir</HI> GEORGE, <HI>and a &s;ervant meeting.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Servant.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir! Sir! Mrs. Darnley is coming here to look for &s;ome books.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's fortunate: did you deliver my me&s;&s;age to her, and her hu&s;band?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Servant.</SPEAKER>
<P>I did, &s;ir, I told them you were gone out of town, and would not return till to mor|row.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very well! then, in ca&s;e of acci|dent, leave open the private door that leads behind the library. <STAGE>(Servant opens a door that leads be|hind the library.)</STAGE> A man of intrigue &s;hould al|ways have a place to lay &s;nug in, and where is he &s;o little likely to be di&s;cover'd, as among&s;t works of &s;tudy and reflection! here &s;he is!
<PB N="65" REF="72">mind we're not interrupted.</P>
<STAGE>(Servant exit&mdash;Sir George retires towards the Library.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Mrs.</HI> DARNLEY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Will Mr. Darnley never be con|vinc'd of this friend's hypocri&s;y! he is &s;o credu|lous, that he even now places more confidence in him, than ever: I'm glad Sir George is out of town&mdash;I can at lea&s;t pa&s;s another hour in peace, and&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(Going towards the Library, Sir George meets her.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't be alarmed, Mrs. Darnley; I'm only a living volume, and if you will pe|ru&s;e my thoughts, you'll read of nothing but your|&s;elf&mdash;you are engraved here in indelible letters, upon my honour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, I was inform'd&mdash;but this is no time for parleying&mdash;alone and unprotected!</P>
<STAGE>(Going, Sir George &s;tvnds in her way.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, you know I have long pro|fe&s;&s;ed a regard for you; long thought you the fine&s;t woman on earth! and as a proof, didn't I offer you my hand, before my friend&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Friend! call him by &s;ome other name, Sir George, and don't profane &s;uch ho|nourable terms.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, isn't he my friend? havn't I &s;o completely gain'd his affections, that he wi&s;hes me to win yours? does he not bring you here&mdash;to my hou&s;e!&mdash;leave me t&ecirc;te-a-t&ecirc;te with you! and in every re&s;pect prove &s;o kind, &s;o obliging&mdash;.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hold, &s;ir&mdash;if he has expo&s;ed me to in&s;ults, I am the per&s;on to accu&s;e him&mdash;not
<PB N="66" REF="73">you! I know his heart, and I know yours&mdash;one has my love&mdash;my e&s;teem&mdash;the other&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Has what, my &s;weet creature?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>My &s;corn.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay then&mdash;I mu&s;t tell you, that when I conde&s;cend to love a woman, I always in&s;i&s;t on making her happy; and therefore, with opportunity on my &s;ide, and the whole world to lay the blame on your hu&s;band&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>On him! the world is not &s;o ea&s;ily deceiv'd! but le&s;t it &s;hould, I'll vindicate his fame&mdash;I'll proclaim the fal&s;ehood of his friend&mdash;his perfidy&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Gently&mdash;gently&mdash;I &s;ee I mu&s;t take advantage now or never!</P>
<STAGE>(Goes to the door.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>What do you mean, &s;ir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fir&s;t to fa&s;ten the door, and then, my angel&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(As he opens it to fa&s;ten it clo&s;ely, Ging|ham enters and pu&s;hes by him.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>And then, my angel&mdash;to give you two hundred pounds&mdash;this note, ma'am, is Mr. Darnley's&mdash;it accidentally fell into my hands, and I de&s;ignedly place it in yours&mdash;put it up, ma'am&mdash;keep it tight in your pocket; for what, with one having a rage for di&s;gui&s;es&mdash;another having a rage for &s;windling&mdash;a third&mdash; <STAGE>(Seeing Sir George.)</STAGE>&mdash;ha! my judge of good breeding! is it you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>This blockhead has ruin'd one &s;cheme already, I &s;ee.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll tell you a &s;ecret Sir George; you <HI>fa&s;hionable</HI> people are very <HI>vulgar</HI>&mdash;it is your fine cloathes, gay equipages, and &s;uperb hou&s;es that are well bred, and not your&s;elves, egad! now only pull off that &s;pangled coat&mdash;&s;tick your|&s;elf behind a counter, and&mdash;.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="67" REF="74">
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, don't you &s;ee I'm bu&s;y?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>To be &s;ure I do.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why don't you leave the room then?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Becau&s;e I've no where el&s;e to go.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then I command you; this lady and I are engag'd.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Engag'd, Sir George!&mdash;Sir, <STAGE>(to Gingham)</STAGE> if you'll conduct me to Mr. Darnley, I &s;hall think my&s;elf a &s;econd time indebted to your gallantry.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Madam, I in&s;i&s;t&mdash; <STAGE>(Cro&s;&s;ing Mrs. D. and taking her by the hand,)</STAGE>&mdash;retire this in&s;tant, Sir&mdash;retire&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! I perceive&mdash;he detains her for ba&s;e purpo&s;es! oh fie! fie!&mdash;fie for &s;hame, Sir George&mdash;is this your good breeding!&mdash;your hand, ma'am&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(Trying to pa&s;s Sir George.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Sdeath&mdash;obey me, or this &s;word, with which I've &s;o often fought.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Often fought! what in earne&s;t?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ra&s;cal! draw.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;I'd rather not.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>What! you don't like to fight!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;who the devil does! but you call me ra&s;cal, &s;ir&mdash;now I've been long in doubt whether I am one or not&mdash;but if I was half as clear on the &s;ubject as you mu&s;t be, I'd own it publickly&mdash;I'd &s;ay, "I Sir George Gauntlet am &s;uch a rude&mdash;ill bred&mdash;vulgar"&mdash;.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Coward!&mdash;come on&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(Drawing his &s;word.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come on!&mdash;well! why &s;houldn't I! I may be alarm'd at ma&s;culine women, but I don't care that&mdash; <STAGE>(Snapping his fingers,)</STAGE>&mdash;for ef|feminate
<PB N="68" REF="75">men! &s;o, though I never learnt to fence in all my life&mdash;though I don't know whether to hold my &s;word in my right hand or my left, have at thee!&mdash;ha!&mdash;ha!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Sir</HI> GEORGE <HI>and</HI> GINGHAM <HI>make two or three pa&s;|&s;es, when loud knocking at the door interrupts them.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Zounds!&mdash;if this &s;hould be Darn|ley&mdash; <STAGE>(looks out.)</STAGE>&mdash;it is! I'm ruin'd&mdash;undone!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, ay, I mu&s;t take le&s;&s;ons&mdash;I'm touch'd&mdash;pink'd&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(&s;haking his hand which is &s;lightly wounded.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>If I &s;tir, I meet Darnley&mdash;hark'ye Sir&mdash; <STAGE>(a&s;ide to Gingham,)</STAGE>&mdash;that lady's hu&s;band is now on the &s;tairs, and your pre&s;ent wound is on|ly a &s;light one; but if you hint or &s;peak one word again&s;t my honour&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>You'll run me through the body I &s;uppo&s;e&mdash;well! as I can't fence&mdash;mum!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hall not leave the room&mdash;I &s;hall be conceal'd, and on the &s;lighte&s;t in&s;inuation, by heaven! I'll come forth and cut you into atoms; promi&s;e&mdash;or&mdash;you know my way&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>I do&mdash;I'll live and fight another day.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Sir</HI> GEORGE <HI>goes behind the Library unperceiv'd by</HI> GINGHAM <HI>or by Mrs.</HI> DARNLEY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>I wi&s;h I knew the name of Sir George's fencing ma&s;ter&mdash; <STAGE>(Mrs. Darnley comes to him)</STAGE>&mdash;my dear ma'am, don't be unea&s;y&mdash;it's only graz'd, and if they don't &s;end doctors and apothecaries to me, I &s;hall live to pink him, again and again.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="69" REF="76">
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Let me bind your hand, with my handkerchief. <STAGE>(Darnley enters behind.)</STAGE> Indeed&mdash;indeed, I owe you much.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(&s;till behind)</STAGE>
<P>'Tis now beyond a doubt&mdash;Oh woman! woman!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(to Mrs. Darnley.)</STAGE>
<P>You hav'nt got the rage&mdash;no, you are what a woman ought to be; mild, gentle, affectionate&mdash;an angel by all that's &s;acred.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>How! make love before my face! &mdash; <STAGE>(advances)</STAGE> So Mrs. Darnley &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnly.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh my dear!&mdash;I'm &s;o glad you're come &mdash; this gallant, generous young man &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Generous young man!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Generous young man!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Has been wounded in my cau&s;e, and &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>And you bound up his arm, with your handkerchief! &mdash;nay, don't deny it, madam&mdash;with my own eyes, I &s;aw it&mdash;well, &s;ir! what have you to &s;ay, &s;ir? to that handkerchief, &s;ir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Say, &s;ir!&mdash;why, I &s;ay, the handker|chief is as fine cambrick as ever was &s;old&mdash;twelve &s;hillings a yard, &s;ir!&mdash;at lea&s;t I u&s;ed to &s;ell &s;uch for a guinea&mdash;a guinea, Mr. Bluff&mdash;as to any thing el&s;e, if you are the lady's hu&s;|band &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I am her hu&s;band, &s;ir!&mdash;who has long lov'd&mdash;long ador'd her!&mdash;and now comes here to witne&s;s her fal&s;ehood and his own di&s;honour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>What does he &s;ay?&mdash;di&s;ho|nour!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, madam&mdash;with him! with this gallant, generous young man! did he not la&s;t night accompany you from the play, and now do I not find you prai&s;ing each other to my very
<PB N="70" REF="77">face?&mdash;ob&s;erve me, Maria&mdash;as you have found me tender in my affections; &s;o you &s;hall find me &s;evere in my re&s;entment.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I know not what he means: but I thought they'd make him hate me&mdash;I guilty of fal&s;ehood! di&s;honour to my hu&s;band! Oh, Harry! if you believe me &s;o debas'd, take up that weapon, and pierce me to the heart!&mdash;in pity do!&mdash;I cannot live and know that you condemn me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(taking her hand.)</STAGE>
<P>Do you not love him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Whom!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Pointing to Gingham.)</STAGE>
<P>Him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Me!&mdash;love me!&mdash;I wi&s;h &s;he did, for if I didn't u&s;e her better than you do, I'd cut my jealous head off!&mdash;look'ye, great lord and ma&s;ter!&mdash;&s;he is more faithful to you, than you de&s;erve&mdash;I know it, becau&s;e ju&s;t before you enter'd the room, Sir George Gauntlet, like a vile &s;educer as he is, was attempting to &mdash; <STAGE>(here a book falls from the library.)</STAGE> crau&mdash;au&mdash;au! <STAGE>(checking him&s;elf.)</STAGE> I &s;hall be a dead man, before I know it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir George Gauntlet!&mdash;paltry eva|&s;ions!&mdash;he is out of town and has &s;o often prov'd him&s;elf a friend. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Friend!&mdash;Oh, Mr. Darnley! at la&s;t I am compell'd to tell you, he is your enemy and mine&mdash;it is that very friend, who would de&s;troy your dome&s;tic peace; who would rob you of a heart, that is, and ever &s;hall be all your own! and that, even now, might have triumph'd o'er a helple&s;s woman, had not his friendly arm been &s;tretch'd to &s;erve me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="71" REF="78">
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>It's true&mdash;I'll &s;wear it!&mdash;I'll&mdash; <STAGE>(another book falls.)</STAGE> crau&mdash;au&mdash;au!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll not believe it&mdash;he is above &s;uch arts, and I would have you, madam, not en|crea&s;e your guilt, by daring to abu&s;e my be&s;t of friends.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Be&s;t of friends!&mdash;upon my &s;oul&punc; you've a rare &s;et of acquaintance then.&mdash;Sir! I always had a knack at &s;peaking what comes up|permo&s;t, and I &s;ay, Sir George wanted to turn me out, in order to lock her in&mdash;I &s;ay, he gave me this wound, in trying to defend her from his in&s;olence&mdash;I &s;ay he is now conceal'd in this room!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(<HI>Books fall from the Library, and leave an open &s;pace.</HI> GINGHAM <HI>looks round, and &s;ees Sir</HI> GEORGE'S <HI>face frowning at him through the aperture.</HI>)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;I don't &s;ay he is in the room&mdash;I don't! becau&s;e&mdash;becau&s;e&mdash; <STAGE>(looking round again)</STAGE> its better to be choak'd then kill'd.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>See how he prevaricates: and there|fore, that my friend may be &s;lander'd and I deceiv'd no longer, 'tis time I &s;hould decide&mdash;Maria!&mdash;It almo&s;t kills me to pronounce it&mdash; <STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE> we meet no more&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>(going.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Holding him.)</STAGE>
<P>Stay&mdash;&s;pare me but a moment&mdash;I cannot&mdash;will not lo&s;e him; Harry, think of our love&mdash;our children. &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir! &s;ir!&mdash;let me a&s;k you two que&s;|tions&mdash; <STAGE>(Another book falls, and Sir George frowns at him.)</STAGE> Ay, grin away you&mdash;Sir! can you &s;ence, and will you fight?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Perhaps, you'll find, I can, &s;ir.</P>
</SP>
<PB N="70" REF="79">
<GAP DESC="duplicate" EXTENT="1 page">
<PB N="71" REF="80">
<GAP DESC="duplicate" EXTENT="1 page">
<SP>
<PB N="72" REF="81">
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>And if I prove that Sir George hid him&s;elf to avoid you, will you &s;tand by, and &s;ee a poor fellow cut to atoms?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;on the contrary, I &s;hall be &s;o convinc'd of the truth of your &s;tory &mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Say you &s;o? then come out you black infernal &s;educer!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(<HI>Runs up to the Library&mdash;forces open the front doors, and amid&s;t the falling of all the books, Sir</HI> GEORGE GAUNTLET <HI>is di&s;cover'd!</HI>)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>There&mdash;there he is! and now come on, if you dare&mdash;here's a pair of the be&s;t fencers in Europe?</P>
<STAGE>(Snatching up a &s;word and placing him|&s;elf by Darnley.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis all unravel'd&mdash;dete&s;ted hypo|crite!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, Darnley!&mdash;how d'ye do!&mdash;this is a droll circum&s;tance, isn't it!&mdash;but I hope you are convinc'd.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, &s;ir, I am convinc'd.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>We're all convinc'd, &s;ir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>That you and Lady Sarah have join'd in a con&s;piracy to deceive me and betray my wife; that you have meanly put on the ma&s;k of friend|&s;hip, to conceal the blacke&s;t artifices, and that if you had come to my hou&s;e and boldly plun|der'd me of all my fortune&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>He'd only have been hang'd!&mdash;but now he &s;hall be cut to atoms.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Be cautious in your language, Mr. Darnley&mdash;you know my di&s;po&s;ition.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I do&mdash;I know you well: and hence|forth if you dare, either by action, word, or look; mark me, &s;ir&mdash;rai&s;e but a blu&s;h in her un&s;ullied
<PB N="73" REF="82">cheek, I will re&s;ent it&mdash;I'll inflict a puni&s;hment, great as your arrogance de&s;erves!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Arrogance!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, arrogance!&mdash;are you deaf!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir George.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, this requires an explanation; you &s;hall hear from me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pooh!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Delay not then, for I &s;hall leave your hou&s;e this moment, <STAGE>(Sir George exit.)</STAGE>&mdash;come Ma|ria&mdash;to you and this gentleman I have a thou&s;and apologies&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ble&s;s you! I'm amply paid in letting my tongue wag&mdash;and as to any thing el&s;e, allow me once more to &s;peak my mind to your &s;weet cou&s;in, Clara! come let's go to her&mdash;Oh! you well bred ruffian!&mdash;to be fir&s;t pink'd, and then nearly choak'd by &s;uch a &mdash;; on the whole, though, I never fought better in all my life!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Exeunt.</STAGE>
</DIV3>
