<DIV2 N="5" TYPE="act">
<PB N="74" REF="83">
<HEAD>ACT V.</HEAD>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="scene">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE I.</HI>&mdash;A Room in a Tavern&mdash;Dinner under Covers&mdash;Darnley di&s;cover'd &s;itting at the Table&mdash; Waiter attending.</HEAD>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Tell Sir George Gauntlet, Mr. Darn|ley is waiting&mdash;what's o'clock?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Waiter.</SPEAKER>
<P>Six, &s;ir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>The time draws near&mdash;I wonder where my friend can be? put &s;ome wine on the table and leave me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Waiter.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir George is below, in clo&s;e conver|&s;ation with a gentleman, who &s;eems anxious to &s;ee you, &s;ir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>His &s;econd, I &s;uppo&s;e&mdash;tell him, I am here&mdash; <STAGE>(Waiter exit.)</STAGE> 'Sdeath!&mdash;to what have I reduc'd my&s;elf?&mdash;I that had every joy this world can give&mdash;a peaceful home&mdash;a wife that lov'd, and children that rever'd me!&mdash;I to be now in a tavern, on the eve of meeting with a pro|fe&s;s'd duelli&s;t? to be about to commit murder, or el&s;e to live di&s;honour'd and di&s;grac'd&mdash;Oh, Maria!&mdash;when thou &s;halt hear thy hu&s;band is no more, wilt thou forgive me?&mdash;wilt thou&mdash; but my fate determines hers, and if I fall &s;he is for ever lo&s;t!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Re-enter the Waiter.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Waiter.</SPEAKER>
<P>The gentleman from Sir George Gaunt|let, &s;ir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="75" REF="84">
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Admit him&mdash;now then for the event!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> GINGHAM <HI>ha&s;tily.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'm &s;o fag'd&mdash;&s;o completely knock'd up <STAGE>(&s;ees the dinner.)</STAGE> ha, ha! what's here?&mdash;the very thing to revive me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>I hope, &s;ir, you haven't been talk|ing to Sir George.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, but I have though&mdash;you em|ploy'd me as &s;econd, and if you're &s;hot, it &s;hall be in the way I like be&s;t. <STAGE>(&s;itting down)</STAGE> Waiter! waiter!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Waiter.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(To Gingham, who is going to pull off a cover of one of the di&s;hes.)</STAGE>
<P>Sir! &s;ir!&mdash;Sir George order'd that di&s;h not to be touch'd till he came.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Did he?&mdash;then it's the pick'd thing I &s;uppo&s;e, &s;o I'll eat it all up directly, <STAGE>(uncovers it, and &s;ees a brace of pi&s;tols laying 'mid&s;t powder and ball.)</STAGE> here&mdash;it's quite at his &s;ervice, and I wi&s;h the whole were in his &s;tomach with all my &s;oul!&mdash; <STAGE>(giving the di&s;h to the waiter, and uncover|ing another.)</STAGE> Ah! here's &s;omething that I can &s;wallow. <STAGE>(begins eating.)</STAGE> Well after hunting every where for Sir George, I found him below &s;tairs at la&s;t&mdash;"&s;o" &s;ays I "my little Librarian"&mdash;al|luding to the book-ca&s;e you know&mdash;"when are you and this jealous hu&s;band"&mdash;alluding to you, you know&mdash;"to fight this fooli&s;h duel?" <STAGE>(drinks a gla&s;s of wine.)</STAGE> Clara! my dear Clara Sedley!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, &s;ir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Says I "the fact is this; one will be kill'd, the other be hang'd, and the world get rid of two hot-headed fellows:" &s;ays he, "Will
<PB N="76" REF="85">Darnley make me an apology?" &s;ays I "he might as well."</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>You did not!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, but I did though "it's very well for fa&s;hionable hu&s;bands, to leave their wives with friends, in hopes of getting divorces and damages; but what right," &s;ays I, "has a country &s;quire to quit his farm, and tru&s;t his wife, with baronets, fools, and coxcombs?&mdash; to plant his own horns" &s;ays I! <STAGE>(drinks.)</STAGE> "Suc|ce&s;s to trade."</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>And how did this end, &s;ir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>How!&mdash;why the other &s;econd in|terfer'd&mdash;&s;aid Sir George could'nt fire at you, and advi&s;ed him to apologize&mdash;he he&s;itated&mdash; I put my hand on my &s;word&mdash;reminded him of my fine fencing&mdash;he &s;ign'd this paper&mdash;I've al|ready &s;hewn it to Mrs. Darnley, and &s;o&mdash; <STAGE>(drinks)</STAGE> Here's the child that has two fathers!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Reading the paper.)</STAGE>
<P>'Tis ample, final &s;atisfaction&mdash;wasn't my Maria happy?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>She was&mdash;but with women, grief &s;oon follows joy, you know&mdash;&s;he &s;ays, your un|cle, whoever he is, has order'd you to quit Bath, and go abroad&mdash;that &s;he is to be left behind, and as your fortune is exhau&s;ted, &s;he fears you mu&s;t con&s;ent&mdash;I'm &s;orry I'm pinch'd too&mdash;however&mdash; <STAGE>(drinks.)</STAGE> Here's confu&s;ion to your &s;tingy old uncle!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Unfeeling! per&s;ecuting man!&mdash;&s;eparate me from all I love&mdash;I know the motive for this barbarous conduct&mdash;he has found a &s;on, on whom he means to lavi&s;h all his favours, and while he rolls in luxury, I and my family may &s;tarve &mdash;may&mdash;but he comes.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="77" REF="86"><HI>Enter Sir</HI> PAUL PERPETUAL.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>So Mr. Darnley: how dare you in|trude into the hou&s;es of great people, and thus repeatedly di&s;grace me?&mdash;look'ye, &s;ir&mdash;I have made up my mind&mdash;you mu&s;t &s;eek your fortune abroad&mdash;I'll pay your expences to the continent, and le&s;t your family &s;hould be a burthen to you, I'll provide for your wife at home.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, &s;ir! do not part us!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>I will!&mdash;I'm re&s;olv'd! <STAGE>(&s;eeing Ging|ham.)</STAGE> hah!&mdash;what do I &s;ee?&mdash;my boy!&mdash;my darling!&mdash;how came you here you rogue?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Father, you're come in time&mdash;ju&s;t in time to fini&s;h the bottle! <STAGE>(filling him a humper, and putting it in his hand)</STAGE> drink! drink the la&s;t toa&s;t!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, what is it?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>"Confu&s;ion to Darnley's"&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>With all my heart&mdash;"confu&s;ion to Darnley's"&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>"Stingy old uncle!"</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(spitting out the wine.)</STAGE>
<P>Stingy old uncle!&mdash;why that's confu&s;ion to my&s;elf you dog!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>What! is it you&mdash;well! hang me if I didn't think it was my father&mdash;that is my other father, the money-lender&mdash;cou&s;in&mdash;rela|tion&mdash;how are you!</P>
<STAGE>(&s;haking Darnley by the hand.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>Non&s;en&s;e! never mind him&mdash;I've brought you your commi&s;&s;ion&mdash;a company in a regiment &s;erving in Ireland.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Have you! <STAGE>(to Sir Paul.)</STAGE> who'd have thought my father was your mi&s;erly uncle, heh!</P>
<STAGE>(to Darnley.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="78" REF="87">
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>It's three hundred a-year, my boy! p&s;ha! don't mind him I tell you, <STAGE>(pulling him away from Darnley.)</STAGE> I re&s;erve every thing for you&mdash;I always meant to give all I could to my &s;on.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Did you!&mdash;Oh then it comes to the &s;ame point; why, perhaps, you'll give me two hundred pounds.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, that I will.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>What! and the commi&s;&s;ion too!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, and the commi&s;&s;ion too! here they are both&mdash;and &s;ome ten years hence, I'll join the regiment, and &s;erve under you; un|der my brave &s;on!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;under your brave nephew if you like&mdash;I don't under&s;tand the exerci&s;e, and Darnley does! and therefore, as we're all rela|tions&mdash;all in a family, I'll e'en give him the commi&s;&s;ion&mdash;Nay, don't be &s;hy cou&s;in&mdash;it makes no difference father, does it?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>Death and fire! it does, &s;ir, it makes all the difference, and I &s;wear&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Softly&mdash;you can make me a hero in another way&mdash;as I was brought up to trade, pop me into the train bands&mdash;then I can be kill'd in the artillery ground in one day, and be alive in the &s;hop the next! &s;o keep the commi&s;&s;ion, cou&s;in; keep it&mdash; <STAGE>(Forcing it into Darnley's hand.)</STAGE> and here&mdash;here's the money to take you, your wife and children to Ireland&mdash; <STAGE>(giving the bank notes.</STAGE>&mdash;there! now moderate your joy, father! you've done a kind, generous action to be &s;ure: but why! why in &s;uch an ec&s;tacy!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ec&s;tacy! agony you puppy!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Gently, gently, at the public break|fa&s;t I &s;hall &s;ound forth your prai&s;es&mdash;come,
<PB N="79" REF="88">cou&s;in&mdash;the be&s;t of the joke is, I've another fa|ther; and though he wont lend you a &s;hilling, I'll make him &s;end you linen enough to &s;hirt your whole regiment.&mdash;Farewell, thou liberal man!&mdash; look!&mdash;Self-gratification has brought tears of joy into his eyes!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(Exit with Darnley.)</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>Tears of joy!&mdash;if being cheated out of my money, makes me cry for plea&s;ure, what &s;hall I do, if I get it back again?&mdash;was there ever &s;uch a fellow?&mdash;however the com|mi&s;&s;ion is of no u&s;e to Darnley&mdash;but then the two hundred pounds&mdash;and the ea&s;e with which he did it.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter a Servant.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Servant.</SPEAKER>
<P>A letter from your Ward, Sir Paul. It requires an immediate an&s;wer.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Reading it.)</STAGE>
<Q>Sir, I am now at the Public Breakfa&s;t, where Mi&s;s Savage ac|tually in&s;i&s;ted on my coming. I have di&s;cover|ed a deep plot of Mr. Savage's, and when I tell you, I am in danger of being run away with, without my con&s;ent, I'm &s;ure you will fly to the relief of your&mdash;Affectionate Ward, CLARA SEDLEY.</Q>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll come directly&mdash; <STAGE>(Servant exit.)</STAGE>&mdash; So&mdash;So&mdash;they have heard of her &s;udden acqui|&s;ition of fortune&mdash;of the Copper Mines being di&s;covered on her e&s;tate, and now like true &s;ava|ges, they mean to paw the property&mdash;but I've a hu&s;band for her in my eye. She has formed an affection for this liberal &s;on of mine, and the dog can't take <HI>her</HI> for a man in woman's cloathes.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="80" REF="89"><HI>Enter</HI> FLUSH.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>You knave!&mdash;if I catch you&mdash;how! has he left the tavern!&mdash;Ah! Sir Paul!&mdash;pray Sir, have you &s;een any thing of my &s;on?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>I know nothing of your &s;on, &s;ir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>He has been di&s;tributing my property&mdash; giving away my money, Sir Paul.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Gad! My &s;on has been doing me the &s;ame favour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, &s;ir; but my &s;on has &s;windled me out of two hundred pounds.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's the exact &s;um!&mdash;my &s;on has &s;windled me out of&mdash;&s;o let's &s;hake hands and cry for joy!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, well&mdash;I can afford it&mdash;but, Sir Paul, there is only one way he can make me retribution&mdash;you've heard of our ward's copper mines, and though you have only known me as a private gentleman, and I you as joint guar|dian&mdash;yet I think you will con&s;ent to her marrying the man I propo&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>And pray, who may the gentleman be?&mdash;not the Honourable Mr. Savage, I hope, for he has no property, but my two racers.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;no&mdash;my Son!&mdash;my rogue of a Son!&mdash;will you agree?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why I would with plea&s;ure only&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>What Brother Guardian?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>I mean to propo&s;e my rogue of a &s;on.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your &s;on!&mdash;why how came you by a &s;on?&mdash;but to the point&mdash;my boy has won her heart, Sir Paul.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>So has mine too, Mr. Flu&s;h.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="81" REF="90">
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yours too!&mdash;Sdeath, Sir Paul&mdash;this racing has turned your brain.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>Racing!&mdash;Iv'e done with it, &s;ir&mdash; I hate it&mdash;I'm above the turf now.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Above the turf!&mdash;I wi&s;h you were under it!&mdash;do you pretend &s;he loves both our &s;ons?&mdash;two men at the &s;ame time, &s;ir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>To be &s;ure&mdash;&s;he's not the fir&s;t wo|man that has lov'd twenty at the &s;ame time, &s;ir&mdash; but as &s;he can't marry without our joint con&s;ent, and is now in great di&s;tre&s;s at Lady Sarah Sa|vage's public breakfa&s;t, let's adjourn there di|rectly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>With all my heart&mdash;I can afford it&mdash; Publick breakfa&s;t!&mdash;why this is later than u&s;ual&mdash; <STAGE>(Looking at his Watch)</STAGE>&mdash;Nine o'clock at night!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, the&s;e are late hours: but what need we care, Mr. Flu&s;h?&mdash;we that have health, youth, &s;pirits&mdash;do you know there is only one hou&s;e in England that affects my con&s;titution?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>And what hou&s;e is that?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Whi&s;pers him.)</STAGE>
<P>I never was there but twice&mdash;the fir&s;t time there was a motion about relieving poor in&s;olvent debtors, and the hou&s;e was &s;o empty I got an ague. The next time, &s;omebody mov'd to remove the hackney coaches from Bond-Street, and the benches were &s;o cram'd that I was thrown into a &s;ever!&mdash;So hey for the breakfa&s;t.&mdash;Youth's the &s;ea&s;on made for joy!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Love is then our duty! &amp;c.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>(Exeunt &s;inging together.)</STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="scene">
<PB N="82" REF="91">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE II.</HI>&mdash;A garden at Mr. Savage's on Lan&s;|aown hill&mdash;a marquee at the upper wing, in which is &s;een a table full of fruits, wine, meat, tea urns, coffee pots, &amp;c. A di&s;tant view of Bath&mdash;moon ri&s;ing.&mdash;Long flouri&s;h of clarinets!</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Lady</HI> SARAH SAVAGE <HI>and a Servant.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>Call Mi&s;s Clara&mdash; <STAGE>(Servant enters marquee.)</STAGE>&mdash;I have given this party in order to &s;ecure this young creature and her fortune, for my bruti&s;h brother has &s;o le&s;&s;en'd our gold, that only her copper can &s;ave us from &s;inking&mdash;if her guardians refu&s;e, we are prepar'd for bolder &s;chemes.
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> CLARA.</STAGE> Well: my dear girl, how do you like our break|fa&s;t? &mdash;breakfa&s;t by moonlight? isn't it quite charming&mdash;&s;o nouv&ecirc;lle?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>Quite&mdash;and in addition to tea and coffee, here are fowls, fruit, and wine, &s;o that you may breakfa&s;t, dine, drink tea, and &s;up all in the &s;ame meal&mdash;nouv&ecirc;lle!&mdash;&s;urely nobody el&s;e is &s;o &s;ingular.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>I don't know&mdash;I never copy&mdash;the world's &s;o very ignorant&mdash;that only act unlike other people, and you're pretty &s;ure of being right, but, didn't you like the mu&s;ic&mdash;the &s;inging?&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>No; I don't much like the&s;e &s;ine &s;ing|ers &mdash;it's a long time before you prevail on them to &s;ing, and then when they once begin&mdash;faith! they never &s;top. I declare I only &s;aw one per&s;on I liked among&s;t the party.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="83" REF="92">
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>And who was that?&mdash;the dear Signor!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;the dear creature, my guardian's &s;on.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>What! that mon&s;ter? I wonder who invited &s;uch a heterogeneous animal, and you to prefer him&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>Even to your brother, Ma'am&mdash;I know Mr. Savage de&s;igns me his hand; but, if my guardians will agree&mdash;and why they leave me in this &s;cene of danger when I wrote to Sir Paul&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady Sarah.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here they are both&mdash;I'll go call my brother, and by the time I return, I hope I &s;hall call you &s;i&s;ter&mdash;adieu!&mdash;Gingham, in|deed!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Sir</HI> PAUL <HI>and</HI> FLUSH.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here &s;he is&mdash;here's the girl to an&s;wer for her&s;elf&mdash;now be cool, Sir Paul&mdash;compo&s;e your&s;elf, and I'll fairly put the que&s;tion to her. Clara, haven't you fix'd your affections?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>To confe&s;s the truth, I have, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Very well&mdash;&s;oftly, Sir Paul! and now, what is the Gentleman's name?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, what is his name, Clary?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>Gingham, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>There! I told you &s;o&mdash;it's my &s;on!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why there! I told you &s;o&mdash;it's my &s;on!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your &s;on!&mdash;In the fir&s;t place I don't believe you have a &s;on; and in the next, do you pretend that this Gingham&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is my boy! my own darling child!&mdash; and I'll prove it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="84" REF="93">
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, well, if this is the ca&s;e. I'll make you a fair propo&s;ition, let's call in both our &s;ons, and let the one &s;he prefers be her hu&s;band.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>Agreed&mdash;and I'll bet you a hun|dred pounds &s;he chu&s;es mine.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Done,&mdash;I'll bet you a hundred &s;he chu&s;es mine.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Within the Marquee.)</STAGE>
<P>My life! my love! my Clara!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here he comes!</P>
<STAGE>(Rubbing his Hands.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here he comes</P>
<STAGE>(Rubbing his Hands.)</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Within Marquee)</STAGE>
<P>I cannot live a moment from thee&mdash;I&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>GINGHAM <HI>enters from the Marquee, and, &s;eeing his two fathers together, pau&s;es and &s;tarts.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now, Clara&mdash;Silence, Sir Paul!&mdash;don't you chu&s;e him!&mdash;him!&mdash;for your hu&s;band?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>I do, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Huzza! I've won my bet!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here is a father don't know his own child.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Coming between them)</STAGE>
<P>And here's a child don't know his own father! upon my &s;oul, Gentlemen, I cannot tell which of you had the honour of inventing me; but here I am, and if you have more property to di&s;tribute&mdash;if either of you has another two hundred pounds, I'll di&s;|po&s;e of it &s;o nearly, that tears of joy &s;hall trickle down your cheeks!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(After looking &s;ome time at Sir Paul.)</STAGE>
<P>Sir Paul!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mr. Flu&s;h&mdash;We were joint guar|dians ju&s;t now and&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>And now we're joint fathers it &s;eems.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="85" REF="94">
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>This mu&s;t be the trade&s;man&mdash;a word in private, if you plea&s;e, Sir. <HI>(They enter the Marquee.</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lay your heads together; &s;ettle it as you plea&s;e; for while Clara &s;miles on me, I care not whether I'm &s;on to a haberda&s;her, or heir to the grand Turk.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cara.</SPEAKER>
<P>I hope they won't quarrel&mdash;I fear Mr. Flu&s;h will in&s;i&s;t&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>He in&s;i&s;t!&mdash;ble&s;s you, he'd &s;ell me for half a crown.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Re-enter</HI> FLUSH <HI>and</HI> SIR PAUL</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>He's mine! he's mine! the father knows his own child at la&s;t.&mdash;I never &s;u&s;pected Flu&s;h was clerk to a Lottery Office, and con&s;e|quently little thought he was the trade&s;man who married my Nelly&mdash;'gad! I always took him for a gentleman.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Did you?&mdash;that was very good natur'd of you&mdash;and &s;o you give me up, Mr. Flu&s;h?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, I can afford it.&mdash;The Tunbridge &s;tory is perfectly explain'd, and I have done with you, you rogue&mdash;Your <HI>wi&s;e</HI> father here has pro|mis'd to re&s;tore my papers, &s;o now you may &s;peak truth till you're black in the face.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>May I? &mdash;then I won't; le&s;t other faces &s;hould be of the &s;ame complexion&mdash;but, gentlemen, &s;ince you've found out who I belong to, will you inform me who this lady is to be|long to?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Clara.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, Mr. Flu&s;h&mdash;I'm &s;ure I &s;hall have your con&s;ent&mdash;you are a monied man and have lived with people of rank.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="86" REF="95">
<SPEAKER>Flu&s;h.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your pardon, ma'am, if I had lived with people of rank, I had not been a monied man&mdash;the fact is, I touch ca&s;h wherever I can, and Sir Paul has brib'd me &s;o hand&s;omely, that I have &s;old my con&s;ent&mdash;I have &s;old my ward as well as my &s;on, and for this plain rea&s;on&mdash;I can afford it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>Clary, take his hand, my Girl. <STAGE>(Giv|ing her to Gingham.)</STAGE> The dog has an odd way of &s;peaking his mind, but in&s;tead of checking him, encourage him; many a man only wants to be told of his errors to correct them, and that is my ca&s;e&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your ca&s;e, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, my boy&mdash;&s;ince you talked of &s;elf-gratification bringing tears of plea&s;ure into my eyes, I re&s;olv'd to try the experiment&mdash;I determin'd to retrench my expences, to &s;ell my hounds, di&s;po&s;e of my &s;tud, and &s;ee if I could not lay out my money on rational and &s;olid plea&s;ures; in be&s;towing happine&s;s on two as innocent and injur'd creatures as ever exi&s;ted!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Mr. and Mrs.</HI> DARNLEY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>Niece, your hand&mdash;Darnley for|give what's pa&s;t, and henceforth if I don't prove a friend to you, tell that &s;on of mine to &s;peak his mind to me&mdash;tell him to take another two hundred pounds out of my pocket; nay, di&s;|per&s;e my whole property&mdash;any thing, &s;o you don't drink "Confu&s;ion to a &s;tingy old uncle!"</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, we owe every thing to your &s;on&mdash;he has been our pilot through the &s;torms of fa&s;hion, and if he now &s;ecures to us in|dependence and our cottage&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="87" REF="96">
<SPEAKER>Sir Paul.</SPEAKER>
<P>Independence and a cottage! S'life! you &s;hall have affluence and a farm as large as Sali&s;bury Plain&mdash;I'll come and &s;ee you every &s;ummer! ay! for &s;ixty years to come!&mdash;odsheart! they &s;ay I'm like an old Volcano burnt out! but it's a mi&s;take&mdash;I'm like an Egyptian lamp that flames for ever!&mdash;A'nt I, my boy?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mu&s;t I &s;peak truth, father?&mdash;mum!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Darnley.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(To Sir Paul.)</STAGE>
<P>You have made me the happie&s;t of men, Sir Paul; but you mu&s;t excu&s;e me when I &s;ay, that your &s;on has the fir&s;t and greate&s;t claim&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Gingham.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, Cou&s;in; if you knew me half as well as I know my&s;elf, you would find I have as many faults as any of you.&mdash;But come, let's adjourn from this vulgar fa&s;hionable &s;cene, and while they drink one toa&s;t, we'll give another&mdash;</P>
<Q><L>&mdash;May manners ma&s;culine no more deface</L>
<L>The charms that con&s;titute each female grace.</L>
<L>To man, be bold and daring &s;chemes confin'd,</L>
<L>Woman for &s;ofter pa&s;&s;ions was de&s;ign'd,</L>
<L>And by meek virtue&mdash;to &s;ubdue mankind!</L></Q>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Exeunt.]</STAGE>
</DIV3>
